Lisa made a painting on the Mac.

701
00:35:38,753 --> 00:35:42,054
MALE REPORTER #1: <i>The Macintosh,
Apple's near mythological home computer,</i>

702
00:35:42,055 --> 00:35:45,659
<i>has gotten off to a rocky start in
its battle with industry titan IBM.</i>

703
00:35:45,660 --> 00:35:48,895
FEMALE REPORTER #1: <i>With sales originally
projected to be a million in the first quarter,</i>

704
00:35:48,896 --> 00:35:51,130
<i>Apple has sold only 35,000
of the user-friendly machines</i>

705
00:35:51,131 --> 00:35:53,567
<i>in the months since it's
been available to customers.</i>

706
00:35:53,568 --> 00:35:55,000
MALE REPORTER #2: <i>The
insistence by Steve Jobs</i>

707
00:35:55,001 --> 00:35:56,735
<i>that it have what's
called end-to-end control,</i>

708
00:35:56,736 --> 00:36:01,375
<i>which is a way of saying that it's not compatible
with most outside hardware or software,</i>

709
00:36:01,376 --> 00:36:04,578
<i>is the Shakespearean flaw in a
machine that</i> had <i>potential.</i>

710
00:36:04,579 --> 00:36:07,480
MALE REPORTER #3: <i>Apple Computers
closed two of its factories today</i>

711
00:36:07,481 --> 00:36:08,915
<i>in the wake of disappointing sales.</i>

712
00:36:08,916 --> 00:36:12,152
FEMALE REPORTER #2: <i>Do you know how
many Macs were sold last month? 500.</i>

713
00:36:12,153 --> 00:36:15,054
MALE REPORTER #4: <i>In a move that
surprised some but not all on Wall Street,</i>

714
00:36:15,055 --> 00:36:17,656
<i>the board of directors of
Apple Computers voted today</i>

715
00:36:17,657 --> 00:36:20,060
<i>to fire its cofounder Steve Jobs.</i>

716
00:36:20,061 --> 00:36:22,094
MALE REPORTER #5: <i>Did he
jump or was he pushed?</i>

717
00:36:22,095 --> 00:36:25,931
<i>His ex-boss, Apple CEO John
Sculley, refused to comment.</i>

718
00:36:25,932 --> 00:36:27,933
MALE REPORTER #6: <i>However,
in an exclusive interview,</i>

719
00:36:27,934 --> 00:36:32,038
<i>Steve Wozniak has slammed the
integrity of his old friend Steve Jobs.</i>

720
00:36:32,039 --> 00:36:35,141
<i>He calls Jobs an
insulting and hurtful guy.</i>

721
00:36:35,142 --> 00:36:38,677
FEMALE REPORTER #3: <i>Jobs is hitting back
with a new company and a new computer.</i>

722
00:36:38,678 --> 00:36:40,781
<i>Apple has a new competitor.</i>

723
00:36:40,782 --> 00:36:43,482
<i>Steve Jobs's black cube is
aimed at the education market.</i>

724
00:36:43,483 --> 00:36:45,951
MALE REPORTER #7: <i>Few people have
the ability to make the world wait,</i>

725
00:36:45,952 --> 00:36:50,425
<i>but that is just what Jobs is
doing with his new company, NeXT.</i>

726
00:36:56,097 --> 00:36:58,697
<i>(horse whinnies)</i>

727
00:36:58,698 --> 00:37:00,600
STEVE: <i>Focus seems kind of sharp.</i>

728
00:37:00,601 --> 00:37:02,134
MAN: <i>On the slide?</i>

729
00:37:02,135 --> 00:37:03,904
The floor. The pin spot.

730
00:37:03,905 --> 00:37:05,938
I think we want a sharp focus.

731
00:37:05,939 --> 00:37:09,442
Don't take it personally. Just
not a fan of the circus aesthetic.

732
00:37:09,443 --> 00:37:13,446
All right, let's hold here. We're gonna
have to go up and refocus the instruments.

733
00:37:13,447 --> 00:37:15,882
Just one. The 30 is fine.

734
00:37:15,883 --> 00:37:19,118
While we're holding, there are
well-wishers in the VIP room.

735
00:37:19,119 --> 00:37:20,821
And Woz is here.

736
00:37:20,822 --> 00:37:23,656
Steve Wozniak. Yes.
(chuckles) Thank you very much.

737
00:37:23,657 --> 00:37:25,192
JOANNA: <i>And Andy Hertzfeld.</i>

738
00:37:25,193 --> 00:37:27,594
Andy Hertzfeld. Thank you.

739
00:37:27,595 --> 00:37:30,496
JOANNA: <i>John Sculley is here too.</i>

740
00:37:30,497 --> 00:37:32,466
It's nice that he's here.

741
00:37:32,467 --> 00:37:34,801
STEVE: Really? I don't
think it's very nice at all.

742
00:37:34,802 --> 00:37:37,136
JOANNA: You have to see them.
They wanna pay their respects.

743
00:37:37,137 --> 00:37:39,772
If they were respectful, we'd
all still be at Apple right now.

744
00:37:39,773 --> 00:37:41,475
(scoffs) Look...

745
00:37:41,476 --> 00:37:43,576
If they really wished me well,
they'd keep to themselves.

746
00:37:43,577 --> 00:37:46,112
- Can I tell you something?
- I don't think they do wish me well.

747
00:37:46,113 --> 00:37:48,581
<i>But I'm all right with
that. I'm over Apple.</i>

748
00:37:48,582 --> 00:37:50,817
I got over the Mac and Woz and Sculley,

749
00:37:50,818 --> 00:37:52,752
the same way you get over
your high school sweetheart.

750
00:37:52,753 --> 00:37:54,554
Build a new one.

751
00:37:54,555 --> 00:37:56,755
- Can I tell you something?
- Yes.

752
00:37:56,756 --> 00:37:58,558
You said you wouldn't compete with them,

753
00:37:58,559 --> 00:38:01,862
but you designed a computer
specifically for the education market,

754
00:38:01,863 --> 00:38:03,929
which they putatively own.

755
00:38:03,930 --> 00:38:07,833
So, I think it's cool they're here.

756
00:38:07,834 --> 00:38:10,036
- They're suing me.
- (elevator bell dings)

757
00:38:10,037 --> 00:38:11,605
Still.

758
00:38:11,606 --> 00:38:13,707
It was nice they came.

759
00:38:15,242 --> 00:38:17,176
They're not being magnanimous.

760
00:38:17,177 --> 00:38:19,179
They want it to look
like an amicable divorce.

761
00:38:19,180 --> 00:38:22,047
History doesn't remember Joe
DiMaggio kindly for dumping Marilyn.

762
00:38:22,048 --> 00:38:23,283
MAN: Steve?

763
00:38:23,284 --> 00:38:25,118
(groans)

764
00:38:25,119 --> 00:38:26,920
What's your problem?

765
00:38:26,921 --> 00:38:30,123
I don't know, but I'm sure
it can be traced back to you.

766
00:38:30,124 --> 00:38:33,792
You know, I'm the one who
has to explain you to people.

767
00:38:33,793 --> 00:38:36,830
$100,000 to Paul Rand for a corporate logo

768
00:38:36,831 --> 00:38:39,632
when we didn't even know
what our company made.

769
00:38:39,633 --> 00:38:43,069
A $650,000 mold for the cube,

770
00:38:43,070 --> 00:38:46,172
because God forbid the
angles be 90.1 instead of 90.

771
00:38:46,173 --> 00:38:49,208
I forbid the angles to
be 90.1 instead of 90.

772
00:38:49,209 --> 00:38:51,777
That box could be on
display at the Guggenheim.

773
00:38:51,778 --> 00:38:54,013
Don't give them reason to say to the press

774
00:38:54,014 --> 00:38:55,949
you have a chip on your shoulder.

775
00:38:55,950 --> 00:38:57,717
Will you do that for me?

776
00:38:57,718 --> 00:38:59,319
I don't have a chip on my shoulder.

777
00:38:59,320 --> 00:39:00,953
(chuckling) Okay, okay.

778
00:39:00,954 --> 00:39:04,658
But don't give them a reason to say you do.

779
00:39:04,659 --> 00:39:06,159
I don't.

780
00:39:06,160 --> 00:39:08,228
- That's the right attitude.
- That's not an attitude.

781
00:39:08,229 --> 00:39:10,696
They're gonna call me back in
a minute to look at the light.

782
00:39:10,697 --> 00:39:12,866
- Get one out of the way.
- Fine!

783
00:39:12,867 --> 00:39:16,335
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

784
00:39:16,336 --> 00:39:18,737
- One more thing.
- Sure.

785
00:39:18,738 --> 00:39:21,040
No questions from the press after.

786
00:39:21,041 --> 00:39:23,275
No... Why?

787
00:39:23,276 --> 00:39:26,346
Until I have better
answers, no press avail.

788
00:39:26,347 --> 00:39:30,450
Somebody asks where I am, you just
saw me, and I'll be right back.

789
00:39:32,218 --> 00:39:33,688
Okay.

790
00:39:35,590 --> 00:39:37,857
Who do you want first?

791
00:39:37,858 --> 00:39:41,028
Bring me the face of Steve Wozniak.

792
00:39:49,336 --> 00:39:52,739
- (exhales)
- Hang on.

793
00:39:52,740 --> 00:39:55,174
- I thought you went to school.
- Hang on.

794
00:39:55,175 --> 00:39:57,911
You were supposed to go to school
an hour ago. I thought you left.

795
00:39:57,912 --> 00:40:00,279
I didn't wake up my mom
on time this morning.

796
00:40:00,280 --> 00:40:02,081
It's happened before too.

797
00:40:02,082 --> 00:40:06,152
I wake up with the alarm and then
I get dressed and eat breakfast,

798
00:40:06,153 --> 00:40:08,821
but sometimes I forget to see
what time it is after that.

799
00:40:08,822 --> 00:40:11,690
- Why doesn't your mom just set her own alarm clock?
- It's one of my chores.

800
00:40:11,691 --> 00:40:14,893
I don't understand what that has
to do with why you're still...

801
00:40:14,894 --> 00:40:16,196
Where's your mother?

802
00:40:16,197 --> 00:40:18,297
LISA: <i>She went to find a pay phone.</i>

803
00:40:18,298 --> 00:40:20,199
An hour ago, she said...

804
00:40:20,200 --> 00:40:22,034
You don't have to raise your hand.

805
00:40:22,035 --> 00:40:24,804
- You said it was off by a little.
- It is.

806
00:40:24,805 --> 00:40:26,806
- I just measured it.
- Joanna...

807
00:40:26,807 --> 00:40:28,775
Exactly a foot on all four sides.

808
00:40:28,776 --> 00:40:30,310
There are six sides.

809
00:40:30,311 --> 00:40:32,411
But you're not supposed
to be here right now.

810
00:40:32,412 --> 00:40:35,681
We know if four of the sides
are equal to each other,

811
00:40:35,682 --> 00:40:38,085
the other two must be equal as well.

812
00:40:39,186 --> 00:40:41,388
The top, bottom, right and left

813
00:40:41,389 --> 00:40:43,757
are about a millimeter shorter
than the front and back.

814
00:40:43,758 --> 00:40:45,257
They're not. I measured them.

815
00:40:45,258 --> 00:40:47,793
Lisa, I'm kind of an expert in design.

816
00:40:47,794 --> 00:40:50,897
And that's a 20-cent ruler. You think
there's a chance it could be off?

817
00:40:50,898 --> 00:40:54,433
If I had another ruler, I would measure
this ruler, but I really doubt it's off.

818
00:40:54,434 --> 00:40:58,337
- When your mother comes back, you have to go to school.
- Because it's a ruler!

819
00:40:58,338 --> 00:40:59,973
Why is it off?

820
00:40:59,974 --> 00:41:01,308
- Did you hear what I just said?
- Yes.

821
00:41:01,309 --> 00:41:03,877
Because sometimes it seems like
you just keep saying what you want

822
00:41:03,878 --> 00:41:05,880
without listening.

823
00:41:11,318 --> 00:41:14,154
I'm listening.

824
00:41:14,155 --> 00:41:17,492
- Is there something you need?
- No.

825
00:41:20,461 --> 00:41:22,094
Why isn't it a perfect cube?

826
00:41:22,095 --> 00:41:24,731
- You've asked me before.
- I forget what it is.

827
00:41:26,367 --> 00:41:27,567
It's an optical anomaly.

828
00:41:27,568 --> 00:41:30,837
To the human eye, a perfect
cube doesn't look like a cube,

829
00:41:30,838 --> 00:41:33,373
so we made it roughly a millimeter
shorter than a foot on two sides.

830
00:41:33,374 --> 00:41:34,940
What's an anomaly?

831
00:41:34,941 --> 00:41:36,810
You've asked me that before too.

832
00:41:36,811 --> 00:41:39,412
I don't know why you keep doing that.

833
00:41:42,015 --> 00:41:44,150
It's an exception. Something
that doesn't fit a pattern.

834
00:41:44,151 --> 00:41:45,284
(knocks)

835
00:41:45,285 --> 00:41:47,353
You have to go to school. Come in!

836
00:41:47,354 --> 00:41:49,121
(door opens)

837
00:41:49,122 --> 00:41:51,324
(chuckles) I think you two have met.

838
00:41:51,325 --> 00:41:52,958
Hello, old friend.

839
00:41:52,959 --> 00:41:56,029
- You look well.
- So do you. So do you.

840
00:41:56,030 --> 00:41:59,998
And they're telling me George is
ready for you to look at the focus.

841
00:41:59,999 --> 00:42:01,500
Take a walk with me.

842
00:42:01,501 --> 00:42:03,103
- Is this Lisa?
- Yeah.

843
00:42:03,104 --> 00:42:05,004
- This can't be Lisa.
- It is.

844
00:42:05,005 --> 00:42:07,005
- Lisa's this big.
- They get taller. Come on.

845
00:42:07,006 --> 00:42:08,908
- Do you remember me?
- She doesn't.

846
00:42:08,909 --> 00:42:10,877
I'm your dad's friend Steve Wozniak.

847
00:42:10,878 --> 00:42:15,047
I apologize. I don't remember you.

848
00:42:15,048 --> 00:42:16,415
You're very polite. (chuckles)

849
00:42:16,416 --> 00:42:18,118
- Woz?
- Yeah.

850
00:42:18,119 --> 00:42:19,953
STEVE: Chrisann's at a pay
phone. Would you find her?

851
00:42:19,954 --> 00:42:21,020
JOANNA: Yeah.

852
00:42:21,021 --> 00:42:22,788
- (door opens)
- STEVE: <i>Good turnout.</i>

853
00:42:22,789 --> 00:42:24,223
- WOZNIAK: Great turnout.
- Yeah.

854
00:42:24,224 --> 00:42:27,159
- "Insanely great." (chuckles)
- Insanely great.

855
00:42:27,160 --> 00:42:29,462
This is the first time we
haven't played for the same team.

856
00:42:29,463 --> 00:42:32,031
It's like you're releasing
your first solo album.

857
00:42:32,032 --> 00:42:34,967
I, uh... I appreciate your
inviting me to the launch.

858
00:42:34,968 --> 00:42:36,469
I just want to wipe the slate clean.

859
00:42:36,470 --> 00:42:39,105
That's exactly what I want.
That's why I came backstage.

860
00:42:39,106 --> 00:42:41,841
I want you to know, um,
I'll be out there with you.

861
00:42:41,842 --> 00:42:44,210
Any chance I can get you to
go out there instead of me?

862
00:42:44,211 --> 00:42:46,011
(chuckles) I love you, Steve.

863
00:42:46,012 --> 00:42:47,446
I love you too, Woz.

864
00:42:47,447 --> 00:42:50,415
WOZNIAK: You know, some things were said.

865
00:42:50,416 --> 00:42:52,384
STEVE: They were. They were said in public.

866
00:42:52,385 --> 00:42:55,455
They were published. Were
you pressured to do it?

867
00:42:55,456 --> 00:42:57,322
WOZNIAK: Was I what?

868
00:42:57,323 --> 00:43:03,062
Check it out. It's the orchestra
pit for the San Francisco Opera.

869
00:43:03,063 --> 00:43:05,330
Was I pressured to do it?

870
00:43:05,331 --> 00:43:08,433
I once met Seiji Ozawa at Tanglewood.

871
00:43:08,434 --> 00:43:10,870
A thunderous conductor.

872
00:43:10,871 --> 00:43:12,971
Ungodly artfulness and nuance.

873
00:43:12,972 --> 00:43:17,543
And I asked him what exactly a
conductor does that a metronome can't.

874
00:43:17,544 --> 00:43:20,313
- Surprisingly, he...
- He didn't beat the living shit out of you? (chuckles)

875
00:43:20,314 --> 00:43:24,917
That's right. No, he said, "The
musicians play their instruments.

876
00:43:24,918 --> 00:43:26,819
I play the orchestra."

877
00:43:26,820 --> 00:43:30,056
That feels like something that sounds
good, but doesn't mean anything.

878
00:43:30,057 --> 00:43:34,194
Markkula, Sculley... Did they ask
you to slag me off in the press?

879
00:43:34,195 --> 00:43:36,228
I had reason to be angry.

880
00:43:36,229 --> 00:43:37,964
- Did they?
- Absolutely not.

881
00:43:37,965 --> 00:43:39,399
But they asked you to talk.

882
00:43:39,400 --> 00:43:41,201
Apple was under siege.
You'd just left the company.

883
00:43:41,202 --> 00:43:42,935
Someone had to talk to the press.

884
00:43:42,936 --> 00:43:46,371
I'm right here, Woz. The company left me.

885
00:43:46,372 --> 00:43:49,042
I begged you. I begged you.

886
00:43:49,043 --> 00:43:51,243
The Apple II accounted
for 70% of the revenue.

887
00:43:51,244 --> 00:43:53,846
What did you think was gonna happen?

888
00:43:53,847 --> 00:43:57,217
You didn't care enough about
the Apple II or the Lisa.

889
00:43:57,218 --> 00:43:58,851
Let's be really clear.

890
00:43:58,852 --> 00:44:01,755
I didn't care at all about
the Apple II or the Lisa.

891
00:44:03,122 --> 00:44:05,357
I wasn't pressured to do it.

892
00:44:05,358 --> 00:44:11,897
What I said to the press was an honest,
if tempered, reflection of what I believed.

893
00:44:11,898 --> 00:44:13,933
- Woz.
- Yeah?

894
00:44:13,934 --> 00:44:16,335
What the fuck is on your wrist?

895
00:44:16,336 --> 00:44:19,505
- You wanna know?
- I literally can't wait.

896
00:44:19,506 --> 00:44:21,607
Everyone's gonna be
wearing these in 10 years.

897
00:44:21,608 --> 00:44:24,009
It's a Nixie watch, made using Nixie tubes.

898
00:44:24,010 --> 00:44:26,379
This is actually
40-year-old technology.

899
00:44:26,380 --> 00:44:29,315
Cold cathode tubes. They're
operating at 140 volts.

900
00:44:29,316 --> 00:44:31,317
I tilt my wrist 45
degrees, it's right there.

901
00:44:31,318 --> 00:44:33,085
Hours, minutes and seconds.

902
00:44:33,086 --> 00:44:35,520
The way our minds work. Look at that.

903
00:44:35,521 --> 00:44:38,123
Do me a favor. Set the watch
ahead like you're on a plane

904
00:44:38,124 --> 00:44:39,592
and just changed time zones.

905
00:44:39,593 --> 00:44:41,360
Not a problem.

906
00:44:41,361 --> 00:44:45,899
Unscrew that. Just hit the button.

907
00:44:45,900 --> 00:44:50,435
Excuse me. Flight attendant? The man next
to me would appear to be detonating a bomb.

908
00:44:50,436 --> 00:44:52,404
You think this looks like a bomb.

909
00:44:52,405 --> 00:44:55,342
Even right now, I'm not 100% sure it isn't.

910
00:44:56,443 --> 00:44:59,814
- I think maybe once people get used to it...
- No.

911
00:45:04,584 --> 00:45:07,654
I was angry.

912
00:45:07,655 --> 00:45:10,489
You were saying things about the Apple II,
and the way you were treating the team...

913
00:45:10,490 --> 00:45:14,192
Woz. You get a free pass for life.

914
00:45:14,193 --> 00:45:17,630
I got to get back onstage. We got
two minutes of rehearsal time left.

915
00:45:17,631 --> 00:45:21,601
Do you understand how condescending
that just was? Maybe you don't.

916
00:45:21,602 --> 00:45:24,203
I don't want to see you get dragged
off an airplane in plastic handcuffs.

917
00:45:24,204 --> 00:45:27,473
I get a free pass for life from you?

918
00:45:27,474 --> 00:45:30,542
You give out the pass...
Y-Y-You give them to me?

919
00:45:30,543 --> 00:45:32,344
You're gonna have a stroke, little buddy.

920
00:45:32,345 --> 00:45:35,849
What did you do? What did you do?

921
00:45:37,318 --> 00:45:39,252
Why has Lisa not heard of me?

922
00:45:39,253 --> 00:45:42,721
Shit, man, how many
fourth-graders have heard of you?

923
00:45:42,722 --> 00:45:47,092
You can't write code. You're not
an engineer. You're not a designer.

924
00:45:47,093 --> 00:45:49,328
You can't put a hammer to a nail.

925
00:45:49,329 --> 00:45:50,964
I built the circuit board.

926
00:45:50,965 --> 00:45:53,433
The graphical interface
was stolen from Xerox PARC.

927
00:45:53,434 --> 00:45:57,170
Jef Raskin was the leader of the Mac team
before you threw him off his own project.

928
00:45:57,171 --> 00:46:00,373
Everything... Someone
