What?

1156
00:57:14,814 --> 00:57:16,848
You ready for Sculley?

1157
00:57:16,849 --> 00:57:18,784
Excuse me!

1158
00:57:18,785 --> 00:57:20,685
Lisa!

1159
00:57:20,686 --> 00:57:22,588
You can't shout!

1160
00:57:26,760 --> 00:57:28,662
(elevator bell dings)

1161
00:57:29,796 --> 00:57:31,698
Lisa?

1162
00:57:40,907 --> 00:57:43,477
You have to go.

1163
00:57:44,711 --> 00:57:48,381
It's dangerous up here. That's
why I make other people do it.

1164
00:57:50,115 --> 00:57:52,451
Who are you hiding from, me or your mom?

1165
00:57:52,452 --> 00:57:56,121
I'm not hiding.

1166
00:57:56,122 --> 00:57:58,592
Let's go.

1167
00:58:05,764 --> 00:58:08,299
What were you listening to?

1168
00:58:08,300 --> 00:58:11,870
I'm listening to two
versions of the same song.

1169
00:58:11,871 --> 00:58:15,339
Then when I get to the ends, I
rewind to listen to them again.

1170
00:58:15,340 --> 00:58:18,844
It's the same song, but
the versions are different.

1171
00:58:18,845 --> 00:58:21,380
- What's the song?
- Okay.

1172
00:58:21,381 --> 00:58:24,415
So it's a really old song, and
it's called "Both Sides, Now."

1173
00:58:24,416 --> 00:58:28,821
- "Both Sides, Now"?
- Yeah.

1174
00:58:28,822 --> 00:58:30,888
What's it about?

1175
00:58:30,889 --> 00:58:35,293
It's about... There are three
verses: Clouds, love and life.

1176
00:58:35,294 --> 00:58:39,998
And the person singing is singing
that they used to think of...

1177
00:58:39,999 --> 00:58:41,866
That they used to think about...

1178
00:58:41,867 --> 00:58:44,168
- Clouds, love and life?
- Right.

1179
00:58:44,169 --> 00:58:48,040
One way, yeah, but now they look
at them another way, and they...

1180
00:58:48,041 --> 00:58:53,911
They've come to the conclusion that they
really don't know clouds, love or life at all.

1181
00:58:53,912 --> 00:58:56,415
Those are the exact words.

1182
00:58:56,416 --> 00:58:57,683
Yeah, Joni Mitchell.

1183
00:58:57,684 --> 00:59:01,955
'Cause it's not a really old
song, unless I'm a really old guy.

1184
00:59:03,088 --> 00:59:05,324
You have to go to school now.

1185
00:59:05,325 --> 00:59:08,527
Do you want me to tell you the
differences between the two versions?

1186
00:59:08,528 --> 00:59:09,862
Right now.

1187
00:59:09,863 --> 00:59:13,431
The first version is the kind of
thing that you would call girlish.

1188
00:59:13,432 --> 00:59:15,933
I didn't mean I want to know
the difference right now.

1189
00:59:15,934 --> 00:59:18,402
I meant you have to go to school right now.

1190
00:59:18,403 --> 00:59:20,105
I can stay and watch.

1191
00:59:20,106 --> 00:59:22,373
You are truant. You're committing a crime.

1192
00:59:22,374 --> 00:59:24,976
I'm not gonna miss anything important.

1193
00:59:24,977 --> 00:59:27,880
- How do you know?
- I read ahead.

1194
00:59:27,881 --> 00:59:31,083
The Pilgrims make it to the New World.

1195
00:59:31,084 --> 00:59:32,984
Then the Declaration of Independence.

1196
00:59:32,985 --> 00:59:35,020
Yeah, you skipped a couple centuries.

1197
00:59:35,021 --> 00:59:37,922
Steve? Chrisann's out there.

1198
00:59:37,923 --> 00:59:41,794
(audience clapping and
stomping rhythmically)

1199
00:59:44,798 --> 00:59:46,330
STEVE: Let's go.

1200
00:59:46,331 --> 00:59:48,266
Can I make my case for staying?

1201
00:59:48,267 --> 00:59:50,236
Nope.

1202
00:59:51,271 --> 00:59:54,474
(clapping, stomping grow faster)

1203
01:00:08,822 --> 01:00:11,889
- She was with me.
- Come on. Your dad doesn't want us to stay.

1204
01:00:11,890 --> 01:00:14,960
That's not true. That's not...

1205
01:00:14,961 --> 01:00:17,328
You have to be in school is all.

1206
01:00:17,329 --> 01:00:20,998
I'm committing a crime right now,
and I don't wanna get in trouble.

1207
01:00:20,999 --> 01:00:23,569
You're not in trouble. I was kidding.

1208
01:00:23,570 --> 01:00:25,103
Okay.

1209
01:00:25,104 --> 01:00:27,605
Hey. What was the second version?

1210
01:00:27,606 --> 01:00:30,843
You said the first version was
girlish. What was the second version?

1211
01:00:32,278 --> 01:00:34,045
I can't really think of the word.

1212
01:00:34,046 --> 01:00:35,848
Okay. Well, have a good day at school.

1213
01:00:35,849 --> 01:00:38,217
- Regretful.
- What?

1214
01:00:38,218 --> 01:00:41,118
Like wishing you could go
back and do things different.

1215
01:00:41,119 --> 01:00:43,388
You're too young to be regretful.

1216
01:00:43,389 --> 01:00:45,891
Not me.

1217
01:00:45,892 --> 01:00:48,627
The person singing the song.

1218
01:00:48,628 --> 01:00:52,499
Got it. Regretful. That
makes sense because...

1219
01:00:55,034 --> 01:00:57,537
(whispers) I wanna live with you.

1220
01:01:10,048 --> 01:01:12,150
Six minutes.

1221
01:01:12,151 --> 01:01:14,754
- You want to see Sculley?
- No.

1222
01:01:23,528 --> 01:01:26,931
You know all those times I
told you you needed security?

1223
01:01:26,932 --> 01:01:29,535
Here's why.

1224
01:01:34,273 --> 01:01:37,442
I don't know how it is I've
gotten older and you haven't.

1225
01:01:37,443 --> 01:01:40,478
Some deal with the devil
I was never offered.

1226
01:01:40,479 --> 01:01:43,047
So you know what I've been
thinking for the last four years?

1227
01:01:43,048 --> 01:01:46,685
(scoffs) As it turns out, John, I've
never known what you were thinking.

1228
01:01:46,686 --> 01:01:49,453
No newborn baby has control.

1229
01:01:49,454 --> 01:01:51,389
Do you know what I'm talking about?

1230
01:01:51,390 --> 01:01:53,592
In '84, before the Mac launch. You said...

1231
01:01:53,593 --> 01:01:57,161
- Yeah.
- You said that being adopted meant you didn't have control.

1232
01:01:57,162 --> 01:01:58,496
We're starting in a minute, so...

1233
01:01:58,497 --> 01:02:00,998
Why do people think I fired you?

1234
01:02:00,999 --> 01:02:03,102
It's fine, John. It's all behind us.

1235
01:02:06,639 --> 01:02:09,107
Is it? Hmm?

1236
01:02:09,108 --> 01:02:11,745
Don't play stupid. You can't pull it off.

1237
01:02:13,646 --> 01:02:16,949
You came here to ask me why
people think you fired me?

1238
01:02:16,950 --> 01:02:18,985
Why do people think I fired you?

1239
01:02:20,218 --> 01:02:22,856
Just confirm something for me, okay?

1240
01:02:23,990 --> 01:02:26,024
- You liked the ad, right?
- (chuckles)

1241
01:02:26,025 --> 01:02:27,692
The commercial... "1984." You liked it.

1242
01:02:27,693 --> 01:02:31,029
- JOHN: When are you gonna get furniture?
- It's not an easy process.

1243
01:02:31,030 --> 01:02:33,130
JOHN: It is. You buy a
couch, take it from there.

1244
01:02:33,131 --> 01:02:36,634
I'd be really surprised if you came
here to talk about interior decorating.

1245
01:02:36,635 --> 01:02:38,069
I liked the ad very much.

1246
01:02:38,070 --> 01:02:39,170
- You did?
- You know I did.

1247
01:02:39,171 --> 01:02:41,440
You're a lying son of a
bitch. You tried to kill it.

1248
01:02:41,441 --> 01:02:44,342
- It's time to take a hard look at the Mac.
- It's past time.

1249
01:02:44,343 --> 01:02:48,513
It's overpriced. We
need to drop it to 1,995.

1250
01:02:48,514 --> 01:02:50,449
We need to double the marketing budget,

1251
01:02:50,450 --> 01:02:52,284
put more bodies on an internal hard drive

1252
01:02:52,285 --> 01:02:53,652
and invest in FileServer.

1253
01:02:53,653 --> 01:02:56,321
- Where the hell did you get the idea I tried to kill...
- Lee Clow.

1254
01:02:56,322 --> 01:02:58,089
- Lee's wrong.
- He's lying?

1255
01:02:58,090 --> 01:03:00,257
- He's... mistaken.
- JOHN: Where would the money come from?

1256
01:03:00,258 --> 01:03:02,460
It would come from finally
getting rid of the Apple II.

1257
01:03:02,461 --> 01:03:04,362
The Apple II is the
only thing making money.

1258
01:03:04,363 --> 01:03:07,466
- You agreed with the board.
- I understood the board's concerns, but I...

1259
01:03:07,467 --> 01:03:09,534
The board's concerns that
we didn't show the product?

1260
01:03:09,535 --> 01:03:11,536
- Among other things, but my question was...
- What other things?

1261
01:03:11,537 --> 01:03:14,672
I'm asking because I'm curious.
You said "among other things."

1262
01:03:14,673 --> 01:03:17,442
Among other things, it was
set in a dystopian galaxy.

1263
01:03:17,443 --> 01:03:19,411
It took place on a planet
where we don't live.

1264
01:03:19,412 --> 01:03:21,446
It was dark and the opposite of our brand.

1265
01:03:21,447 --> 01:03:23,681
<i>And</i> we didn't show the product.

1266
01:03:23,682 --> 01:03:27,451
People talked about the ad but most of
them didn't know what we were selling.

1267
01:03:27,452 --> 01:03:29,487
The Mac needs to sell for 1,995.

1268
01:03:29,488 --> 01:03:33,525
There is no market research telling us
the Mac is failing because it's overpriced.

1269
01:03:33,526 --> 01:03:37,429
It's telling us that people don't like it
because they think it doesn't do anything.

1270
01:03:37,430 --> 01:03:39,764
It's closed,
end-to-end.

1271
01:03:39,765 --> 01:03:42,433
We didn't know it wasn't what
people wanted, but it isn't.

1272
01:03:42,434 --> 01:03:44,502
They want slots, they want
choices, they want options.

1273
01:03:44,503 --> 01:03:46,804
The way we buy stereos...
mix and match components.

1274
01:03:46,805 --> 01:03:49,473
John, listen to me. Whoever
said the customer is always right

1275
01:03:49,474 --> 01:03:51,243
was, I promise you, a customer.

1276
01:03:51,244 --> 01:03:53,444
- It had skinheads in it.
- She was liberating them.

1277
01:03:53,445 --> 01:03:56,580
- Liberating the skinheads.
- The ad didn't have anything to do with fucking skinheads.

1278
01:03:56,581 --> 01:03:58,350
We used them as fucking extras.

1279
01:03:58,351 --> 01:03:59,717
Nobody even knows they were skinheads.

1280
01:03:59,718 --> 01:04:02,187
I'm just saying the board had concerns...

1281
01:04:02,188 --> 01:04:04,089
You invented lifestyle advertising.

1282
01:04:04,090 --> 01:04:05,824
And our brand was my brand.

1283
01:04:05,825 --> 01:04:08,627
My job is to make a
recommendation to the board.

1284
01:04:08,628 --> 01:04:09,995
We showed a lot of happy
people drinking Pepsi.

1285
01:04:09,996 --> 01:04:13,498
We didn't say the world was going
to end if you bought a Dr. Pepper.

1286
01:04:13,499 --> 01:04:16,268
Recommend that we drop the price
and double the marketing budget.

1287
01:04:16,269 --> 01:04:18,770
- I can't.
- <i>And</i> we showed the product.

1288
01:04:18,771 --> 01:04:22,473
We showed it being opened, we showed
it being poured, being consumed.

1289
01:04:22,474 --> 01:04:24,643
What are you gonna do,
recommend that we kill the Mac?

1290
01:04:24,644 --> 01:04:27,046
I already have, Steve.

1291
01:04:28,180 --> 01:04:31,149
What? When?

1292
01:04:31,150 --> 01:04:32,717
You think the secret to your success

1293
01:04:32,718 --> 01:04:35,087
was not assuming people knew
what to do with a can of soda?

1294
01:04:35,088 --> 01:04:38,489
I didn't kill the ad, Steve! I'm the
only reason it made it on the air.

1295
01:04:38,490 --> 01:04:40,659
Just now. An hour ago.

1296
01:04:40,660 --> 01:04:42,359
I'm coming from Markkula's house.

1297
01:04:42,360 --> 01:04:45,362
- What did he say?
- (chuckles)

1298
01:04:45,363 --> 01:04:47,466
- What did he say?
- Invent something new.

1299
01:04:47,467 --> 01:04:49,301
I'll give you a team. You can sit in Maui.

1300
01:04:49,302 --> 01:04:50,603
The resorts come with couches.

1301
01:04:50,604 --> 01:04:55,806
Wait a minute. Are you saying you
recommended terminating the Mac

1302
01:04:55,807 --> 01:04:57,775
or you recommended taking
me off the Mac team?

1303
01:04:57,776 --> 01:05:00,812
We bought three spots in the
Super Bowl. Two 30's and a 60.

1304
01:05:00,813 --> 01:05:02,681
After we screened it, the
board wanted that money back

1305
01:05:02,682 --> 01:05:04,616
and they asked me to sell off the spots.

1306
01:05:04,617 --> 01:05:07,118
Chiat/Day sold off the
two 30's but not the 60,

1307
01:05:07,119 --> 01:05:08,552
and I let it be known to Lee Clow

1308
01:05:08,553 --> 01:05:10,788
that if he didn't try very
hard to sell the last spot,

1309
01:05:10,789 --> 01:05:12,424
I wouldn't be unhappy.

1310
01:05:12,425 --> 01:05:14,493
If we drop the price
and double the budget...

1311
01:05:14,494 --> 01:05:16,228
Drop the price or double
the budget. (stammers)

1312
01:05:16,229 --> 01:05:18,763
The only way to do that is to
take money out of the Apple II.

1313
01:05:18,764 --> 01:05:21,533
The Apple II should embarrass
you. It embarrasses me.

1314
01:05:21,534 --> 01:05:23,400
It doesn't embarrass the shareholders.

1315
01:05:23,401 --> 01:05:24,768
I don't give a shit about the shareholders.

1316
01:05:24,769 --> 01:05:27,371
That's why I hired you, so I don't
have to hear about shareholders.

1317
01:05:27,372 --> 01:05:30,808
The shareholders are my problem, and
the board represents the shareholders.

1318
01:05:30,809 --> 01:05:32,676
That's how it works.

1319
01:05:32,677 --> 01:05:35,279
You sure it wasn't Lee Clow who
dragged his feet selling the 60?

1320
01:05:35,280 --> 01:05:37,716
At my direction, Steve.

1321
01:05:37,717 --> 01:05:40,585
You think he would have done that
on his own, taken it on himself?

1322
01:05:40,586 --> 01:05:43,288
Yeah. I think he would've done
what it took to save it from you.

1323
01:05:43,289 --> 01:05:45,824
- I was the only thing protecting it.
- You didn't want the ad

1324
01:05:45,825 --> 01:05:48,859
because you were trying to kill the
Mac two months before it launched.

1325
01:05:48,860 --> 01:05:51,063
You are fucking delusional.

1326
01:05:52,731 --> 01:05:53,831
(sighs)

1327
01:05:53,832 --> 01:05:55,699
- Can I mention something to you?
- Sure.

1328
01:05:55,700 --> 01:05:58,271
I have no earthly idea why you're here.

1329
01:05:59,838 --> 01:06:03,174
The story of why and how you left Apple,

1330
01:06:03,175 --> 01:06:05,911
which is quickly becoming
mythologized, isn't true.

1331
01:06:05,912 --> 01:06:08,413
- I'm gonna take this to the board myself.
- Don't do that.

1332
01:06:08,414 --> 01:06:10,181
- I <i>am</i> doing that.
- You can't.

1333
01:06:10,182 --> 01:06:12,817
Why?

1334
01:06:12,818 --> 01:06:16,122
They believe you're no longer
necessary to this company.

1335
01:06:20,425 --> 01:06:25,563
I get hate mail, death threats.

1336
01:06:25,564 --> 01:06:29,201
I get death threats.

1337
01:06:29,202 --> 01:06:33,072
My kids are getting taunted.
Why do people think I fired you?

1338
01:06:35,340 --> 01:06:36,942
Joanna's gonna call my name in a second.

1339
01:06:36,943 --> 01:06:38,810
- JOANNA: Steve?
- That was unrehearsed.

1340
01:06:38,811 --> 01:06:40,511
Yeah, I'll be there in just a second.

1341
01:06:40,512 --> 01:06:42,746
I gave you your day in court.

1342
01:06:42,747 --> 01:06:44,348
- You gave me?
- I gave the board a clear choice.

1343
01:06:44,349 --> 01:06:47,953
I said, "Do you want to invest in the Apple
II or the Mac?" They chose the Apple II.

1344
01:06:47,954 --> 01:06:50,288
The same people who wanted
to dump the Super Bowl spot.

1345
01:06:50,289 --> 01:06:52,358
And then I got on a plane to China.

1346
01:06:53,892 --> 01:06:56,427
Mr. Sculley. There's a
call for you on Line One.

1347
01:06:56,428 --> 01:06:59,697
Or I almost got on a plane,
because I got a call in the lounge.

1348
01:06:59,698 --> 01:07:01,433
- Who made that call?
- Doesn't matter.

1349
01:07:01,434 --> 01:07:02,967
STEVE: <i>It matters to
me. Who made the call?</i>

1350
01:07:02,968 --> 01:07:04,168
John Sculley.

1351
01:07:04,169 --> 01:07:06,004
MAN (on phone): <i>John? If
you get on that plane,</i>

1352
01:07:06,005 --> 01:07:08,906
<i>you'll have lost your
job by the time it lands.</i>

1353
01:07:08,907 --> 01:07:12,509
<i>Steve's been calling the
board. He wants you out.</i>

1354
01:07:12,510 --> 01:07:15,513
JOHN: <i>I left my bags on the plane.
My shit's still somewhere in Beijing.</i>

1355
01:07:15,514 --> 01:07:18,549
I took a car back to Cupertino in
the middle of the fucking night.

1356
01:07:18,550 --> 01:07:23,355
I know what time it is. I need a quorum
here in one hour and I want Steve here too.

1357
01:07:23,356 --> 01:07:25,857
STEVE: <i>You took me off the
Mac, and it was bad business.</i>

1358
01:07:25,858 --> 01:07:28,726
- The quorum call was a homicide.
- Right there! Right there.

1359
01:07:28,727 --> 01:07:30,462
That's the part that's bullshit, my friend.

1360
01:07:30,463 --> 01:07:31,929
It was a suicide.

1361
01:07:31,930 --> 01:07:34,665
Because you knew your
cards and I showed you mine.

1362
01:07:34,666 --> 01:07:37,534
I showed you mine, and you did it anyway.

1363
01:07:37,535 --> 01:07:38,937
What did you think I was gonna do?

1364
01:07:38,938 --> 01:07:41,605
I'm okay losing, but I'm not gonna forfeit.

1365
01:07:41,606 --> 01:07:44,308
I'm not okay losing.

1366
01:07:44,309 --> 01:07:46,745
JOHN: <i>We're losing market share,
and the Mac is losing money.</i>

1367
01:07:46,746 --> 01:07:51,949
Our only hope is the Apple II, which is stagnating
because of its soon-to-be-obsolete DOS.

1368
01:07:51,950 --> 01:07:55,386
Users are already rigging their machines
to run with a CP/M operating system

1369
01:07:55,387 --> 01:07:56,755
that's been built to run on Intel.

1370
01:07:56,756 --> 01:07:58,857
I can't put it more simply than this.

1371
01:07:58,858 --> 01:08:01,859
We need to put our resources
into updating the Apple II.

1372
01:08:01,860 --> 01:08:04,562
STEVE: <i>By taking
resources from the Mac.</i>

1373
01:08:04,563 --> 01:08:05,964
JOHN: <i>It's failing. That's a fact.</i>

1374
01:08:05,965 --> 01:08:07,998
- It's overpriced.
- There's no evidence that it's...

1375
01:08:07,999 --> 01:08:09,900
I'm the evidence!

1376
01:08:09,901 --> 01:08:13,772
I'm the world's leading expert on
the Mac, John. What's your résumé?

1377
01:08:13,773 --> 01:08:15,706
You're issuing contradictory instructions,

1378
01:08:15,707 --> 01:08:17,709
you're insubordinate,
you make people miserable.

1379
01:08:17,710 --> 01:08:20,844
Our top engineers are
fleeing to Sun, Dell, HP.

1380
01:08:20,845 --> 01:08:22,981
<i>Wall Street doesn't know
who's driving the bus.</i>

1381
01:08:22,982 --> 01:08:25,049
We've lost hundreds of millions in value.

1382
01:08:25,050 --> 01:08:28,686
And I'm the CEO of Apple,
Steve. That's my résumé.

1383
01:08:28,687 --> 01:08:31,522
But before that, you sold
carbonated sugar water, right?

1384
01:08:31,523 --> 01:08:35,427
I sat in a fucking garage with
Wozniak and invented the future.

1385
01:08:35,428 --> 01:08:38,862
Because artists lead and
hacks ask for a show of hands.

1386
01:08:38,863 --> 01:08:39,864
All right.

1387
01:08:39,865 --> 01:08:41,865
Well, this guy's out of control.

1388
01:08:41,866 --> 01:08:44,602
I'm perfectly willing to hand
in my resignation tonight,

1389
01:08:44,603 --> 01:08:46,538
but if you want me to
stay, you can't have Steve.

1390
01:08:46,539 --> 01:08:48,740
Settle him out.

1391
01:08:48,741 --> 01:08:51,843
He can keep a share of stock
so he gets our newsletter.

1392
01:08:51,844 --> 01:08:54,478
<i>He'll have to sever his
connection to Apple.</i>

1393
01:08:54,479 --> 01:08:58,384
I'm dead serious. I want the
secretary to call for a vote.

1394
01:08:59,985 --> 01:09:03,088
I fucking dare you.

1395
01:09:03,089 --> 01:09:08,759
You have done an outstanding job over
the years of cultivating the press.

1396
01:09:08,760 --> 01:09:10,294
And by that, I mean manipulating them.

1397
01:09:10,295 --> 01:09:13,932
Because none of them, none of their
editors, none of their editors' publishers

1398
01:09:13,933 --> 01:09:16,066
to this day know that you forced it,

1399
01:09:16,067 --> 01:09:18,035
<i>that you forced the board.</i>

1400
01:09:18,036 --> 01:09:20,371
<i>Even after I told you
exactly what they'd do,</i>

1401
01:09:20,372 --> 01:09:22,473
which is exactly what they did.

1402
01:09:22,474 --> 01:09:24,875
Unanimously.

1403
01:09:24,876 --> 01:09:27,579
I don't have any trouble
remembering that, John,

1404
01:09:27,580 --> 01:09:31,048
because of it being the
worst night of my life.

1405
01:09:31,049 --> 01:09:34,151
And I forced the vote because
I believed I was right.

1406
01:09:34,152 --> 01:09:37,289
- I still believe I'm right. And I'm right.
- (mutters)

1407
01:09:38,758 --> 01:09:40,525
Now I bled that night.

1408
01:09:40,526 --> 01:09:42,694
<i>And I don't bleed.</i>

1409
01:09:42,695 --> 01:09:44,396
<i>But time's done its thing,</i>

1410
01:09:44,397 --> 01:09:46,998
<i>and I really haven't
thought about it in a while.</i>

1411
01:09:46,999 --> 01:09:51,669
Now, I absolutely
understand why you're upset.

1412
01:09:51,670 --> 01:09:53,737
<i>And I want people to
know the truth too.</i>

1413
01:09:53,738 --> 01:09:55,839
JOANNA: It's time.

1414
01:09:55,840 --> 01:09:57,741
Got it.

1415
01:09:57,742 --> 01:09:59,843
You're gonna end me, aren't you?

1416
01:09:59,844 --> 01:10:02,112
STEVE: You're being ridiculous.

1417
01:10:02,113 --> 01:10:05,482
I'm gonna sit center court
and watch you do it yourself.

1418
01:10:05,483 --> 01:10:09,119
Then I'm gonna order a nice meal with
a '55 Margaux and sign some autographs.

1419
01:10:09,120 --> 01:10:11,856
- Jesus Christ.
- You want some advice, Pepsi Generation?

1420
01:10:11,857 --> 01:10:14,592
Don't send Woz out to slap
me around in the press.

1421
01:10:14,593 --> 01:10:17,195
Anybody else... you, Markkula, Arthur Rock.

1422
01:10:17,196 --> 01:10:18,896
Anyone but Rain Man.

1423
01:10:18,897 --> 01:10:21,432
Don't manipulate him like that.

1424
01:10:21,433 --> 01:10:25,102
Whatever you may think, I'm
always gonna protect him.

1425
01:10:25,103 --> 01:10:27,205
Come on, Steve.

1426
01:10:28,573 --> 01:10:31,176
That's what men do.

1427
01:10:31,177 --> 01:10:33,512
- We can't start late.
- (mutters)

1428
01:10:44,990 --> 01:10:48,494
I don't think there was any way
to detect a chip on my shoulder.

1429
01:10:49,795 --> 01:10:51,295
Did you know, back at Bandley,

1430
01:10:51,296 --> 01:10:55,600
the Mac team gave an award every year
to the person who could stand up to you?

1431
01:10:55,601 --> 01:10:56,734
No.

1432
01:10:56,735 --> 01:11:01,573
- I won. Three years in a row.
- Cool.

1433
01:11:05,210 --> 01:11:06,811
This.

1434
01:11:06,812 --> 01:11:10,882
This... This Guy Kawasaki
in <i>Macworld.</i>

1435
01:11:10,883 --> 01:11:13,651
He accidentally got it right, didn't he?

1436
01:11:13,652 --> 01:11:15,219
You've been dragging
your feet on the NeXT OS

1437
01:11:15,220 --> 01:11:18,623
till you can figure out
what Apple's gonna need.

1438
01:11:18,624 --> 01:11:20,158
(clicks tongue)

1439
01:11:20,159 --> 01:11:23,828
Even if that were true, it doesn't
sound that diabolical to me.

1440
01:11:23,829 --> 01:11:25,530
WOMAN: Hey. We're ready for you.

1441
01:11:25,531 --> 01:11:28,167
(rumbling)

1442
01:11:35,040 --> 01:11:38,543
I'm your closest confidante,
your... your best friend.

1443
01:11:38,544 --> 01:11:41,713
Your thing... What do you call it?

1444
01:11:41,714 --> 01:11:43,882
Your work wife. The whole time.

1445
01:11:43,883 --> 01:11:45,883
The last three years.

1446
01:11:45,884 --> 01:11:47,887
(rumbling continues)

1447
01:11:49,921 --> 01:11:55,660
When did you change your mind and start
building the Steve Jobs Revenge Machine?

1448
01:11:55,661 --> 01:11:58,629
(sighs)

1449
01:11:58,630 --> 01:12:00,697
- House to half.
- (rumbling fades)

1450
01:12:00,698 --> 01:12:03,302
You remember Skylab?

1451
01:12:05,070 --> 01:12:10,941
It was an unmanned satellite NASA sent up in
the early '70s on a data gathering mission.

1452
01:12:10,942 --> 01:12:13,611
The thing is, when they sent it up,

1453
01:12:13,612 --> 01:12:16,146
they didn't know yet how
they were gonna get it back.

1454
01:12:16,147 --> 01:12:18,182
But they felt like they were close enough

1455
01:12:18,183 --> 01:12:21,619
<i>that in the eight years it was gonna
be up there, they'd figure it out.</i>

1456
01:12:21,620 --> 01:12:23,087
WOMAN: They're on their way now.

1457
01:12:23,088 --> 01:12:25,822
They didn't.

1458
01:12:25,823 --> 01:12:27,892
So after eight years, it came crashing down

1459
01:12:27,893 --> 01:12:30,561
in a thousand-mile swath
across the Indian Ocean.

1460
01:12:30,562 --> 01:12:32,996
- (audience cheering)
- <i>A little to the left, a little to the right,</i>

1461
01:12:32,997 --> 01:12:34,966
<i>somebody could have gotten hurt.</i>

1462
01:12:34,967 --> 01:12:39,102
I really wanted to build
a computer for colleges.

1463
01:12:39,103 --> 01:12:41,705
The technology just didn't catch
up as fast as I needed it to.

1464
01:12:41,706 --> 01:12:43,975
<i>You know we're out of money.</i>

1465
01:12:43,976 --> 01:12:46,276
MAN (on PA): <i>Ladies and gentlemen, the
program will be starting momentarily.</i>

1466
01:12:46,277 --> 01:12:49,580
STEVE: <i>But then Apple stopped
innovating, and I saw something better.</i>

1467
01:12:49,581 --> 01:12:54,718
Joanna, I know schools aren't gonna buy
a $13,000 dictionary with good speakers.

1468
01:12:54,719 --> 01:12:56,755
You know I know that.

1469
01:12:58,590 --> 01:13:00,258
But Apple will.

1470
01:13:00,259 --> 01:13:03,828
'Cause Avie Tevanian is gonna
build them exactly the OS they need.

1471
01:13:03,829 --> 01:13:06,731
<i>They're gonna have to buy me too.</i>

1472
01:13:06,732 --> 01:13:12,671
For half a billion dollars in stock
and end-to-end control on every product.

1473
01:13:14,740 --> 01:13:16,642
(scoffs)

1474
01:13:19,178 --> 01:13:22,648
(applause continues)

1475
01:13:30,356 --> 01:13:32,457
(no audible dialogue)

1476
01:13:43,402 --> 01:13:47,372
WOMAN: Ladies and
gentlemen, please welcome...

1477
01:13:51,009 --> 01:13:54,277
FEMALE REPORTER: <i>More than a year after it
was first unveiled to industry insiders,</i>

1478
01:13:54,278 --> 01:13:57,014
<i>the NeXT Computer is
finally available in stores.</i>

1479
01:13:57,015 --> 01:14:00,752
MALE REPORTER #1: <i>And it appears to be
two strikes in a row for Steve Jobs.</i>

1480
01:14:00,753 --> 01:14:02,186
MALE REPORTER #2:
<i>Students and educators</i>

1481
01:14:02,187 --> 01:14:05,289
<i>are finding it difficult to
justify the machine's high cost.</i>

1482
01:14:05,290 --> 01:14:07,191
FEMALE REPORTER #2: <i>So
much for the black cube.</i>

1483
01:14:07,192 --> 01:14:12,129
<i>NeXT just sold its factory to Canon
and laid off half its employees.</i>

1484
01:14:12,130 --> 01:14:15,165
In the world of computers,
it's kill or be killed.

1485
01:14:15,166 --> 01:14:17,301
Apple Computer has fallen on hard times.

1486
01:14:17,302 --> 01:14:20,103
It is laying off about 2,500 people.

1487
01:14:20,104 --> 01:14:22,306
FEMALE REPORTER #3: <i>Apple is
continuing to lose market share,</i>

1488
01:14:22,307 --> 01:14:25,142
<i>with no new innovations in the
pipeline except the Newton,</i>

1489
01:14:25,143 --> 01:14:27,678
<i>a pet project of CEO John Sculley.</i>

1490
01:14:27,679 --> 01:14:30,947
MALE REPORTER #3: <i>If you really want
to be mobile, you want a Newton PDA.</i>

1491
01:14:30,948 --> 01:14:32,417
<i>But then again, maybe you don't.</i>

1492
01:14:32,418 --> 01:14:35,753
MALE REPORTER #4: <i>It turns
handwriting into computer text.</i>

1493
01:14:35,754 --> 01:14:39,692
Hey, Dolph, take a memo on
your Newton. "Beat up Martin."

1494
01:14:41,393 --> 01:14:43,261
- Bah!
- (yelps)

1495
01:14:43,262 --> 01:14:46,030
FEMALE REPORTER #4: <i>In 1980,
Apple had 30% of the market.</i>

1496
01:14:46,031 --> 01:14:48,766
<i>Today, Apple has only 3.2 percent.</i>

1497
01:14:48,767 --> 01:14:52,604
MALE REPORTER #5: <i>That's it. John
Sculley has been fired from Apple.</i>

1498
01:14:53,938 --> 01:14:56,708
DAVID LETTERMAN: What about this Internet
thing? Do you know anything about that?

1499
01:14:56,709 --> 01:14:59,444
It is the big new thing.

1500
01:14:59,445 --> 01:15:02,079
Rumors are flying around
Apple Computer once again

1501
01:15:02,080 --> 01:15:03,714
over who will take over the helm.

1502
01:15:03,715 --> 01:15:06,383
In the news at this hour, a
remarkable high-tech reunion.

1503
01:15:06,384 --> 01:15:09,020
FEMALE REPORTER #5: <i>Well, it's
happening. In a billion-dollar shakeup,</i>

1504
01:15:09,021 --> 01:15:12,123
<i>Apple is purchasing NeXT Computer's
operating system, which may mean...</i>

1505
01:15:12,124 --> 01:15:14,726
- MALE REPORTER #6: <i>Is the prodigal son returning?</i>
- FEMALE REPORTER #6: <i>Bet on it.</i>

1506
01:15:14,727 --> 01:15:16,861
Guess what. Mac is back.

1507
01:15:16,862 --> 01:15:18,428
- Apple cofounder Steven Jobs...
- Steve Jobs...

1508
01:15:18,429 --> 01:15:20,330
- Steve Jobs...
- Steve Jobs...
- Steve Jobs...

1509
01:15:20,331 --> 01:15:22,901
FEMALE REPORTER #7: <i>Steve
Jobs is returning to Apple.</i>

1510
01:15:24,469 --> 01:15:27,472
STEVE: <i>If you want to beam your digital
photographs from your digital camera,</i>

1511
01:15:27,473 --> 01:15:29,173
<i>it's built into every product.</i>

1512
01:15:29,174 --> 01:15:31,275
<i>We're going to the
new generation of I/O.</i>

1513
01:15:31,276 --> 01:15:34,178
Twelve megabyte USB. Two ports.

1514
01:15:34,179 --> 01:15:36,748
We're leaving the old Apple I/O behind.

1515
01:15:36,749 --> 01:15:39,383
Stereo surround sound
built into every product,

1516
01:15:39,384 --> 01:15:43,353
a great keyboard and the
coolest mouse you've ever seen.

1517
01:15:43,354 --> 01:15:47,424
- This time, we used actual mice.
- (laughter)

1518
01:15:47,425 --> 01:15:50,895
We're opening the house
in 10 minutes. Steven?

1519
01:15:50,896 --> 01:15:52,530
Do you want to stop horsing around?

1520
01:15:52,531 --> 01:15:57,000
Bless my eyes. That's Steve
Wozniak sitting out there.

1521
01:15:57,001 --> 01:16:00,003
(applause, cheering)

1522
01:16:00,004 --> 01:16:03,441
Give yourselves a treat and ask Woz
if he happens to have the correct time.

1523
01:16:03,442 --> 01:16:07,410
- (laughter)
- I have the correct time, and we're running out of it.

1524
01:16:07,411 --> 01:16:11,348
- "A great keyboard"...
- A great keyboard and the coolest mouse you've ever seen.

1525
01:16:11,349 --> 01:16:14,785
- This is what those things look like today.
- (all groaning)

1526
01:16:14,786 --> 01:16:19,456
Now, I'd like to show you what
they're gonna look like tomorrow.

1527
01:16:19,457 --> 01:16:22,360
This is the iMac.

1528
01:16:22,361 --> 01:16:24,962
(applause, cheering)

1529
01:16:24,963 --> 01:16:27,700
<i>♪♪ (instrumental on speakers)</i>

1530
01:16:42,180 --> 01:16:44,782
(applause, cheering continue)

1531
01:16:51,823 --> 01:16:53,324
- <i>♪♪ (ends)</i>
- That was cool.

1532
01:16:53,325 --> 01:16:55,426
Why did I like that
better than I usually do?

1533
01:16:55,427 --> 01:16:57,494
- JOANNA: I don't know.
- Something was different.

1534
01:16:57,495 --> 01:16:59,196
ANDREA: Hey, stupid.

1535
01:16:59,197 --> 01:17:01,432
I think she's talking to one of you guys.

1536
01:17:01,433 --> 01:17:04,235
- Did you notice a difference?
- That's what I'm...

1537
01:17:04,236 --> 01:17:06,937
The exit signs were off.

1538
01:17:06,938 --> 01:17:09,472
- Full blackout.
- You did it.

1539
01:17:09,473 --> 01:17:11,843
We wired all the exit lights to our board.

1540
01:17:11,844 --> 01:17:14,378
They go out with the cue for seven
seconds then come back on again. In theory.

1541
01:17:14,379 --> 01:17:18,115
- We think that's legal?
- No, we're very certain it's not.

1542
01:17:18,116 --> 01:17:20,484
- You want to see some quotes?
- Let's hold off on those.

1543
01:17:20,485 --> 01:17:22,253
- No, he'll like 'em.
- (mouths word)

1544
01:17:22,254 --> 01:17:25,758
- I'll show 'em to you later.
- I'll take 'em now.

1545
01:17:27,159 --> 01:17:29,227
- I'm sorry.
- Pick it up from there, please.

1546
01:17:29,228 --> 01:17:31,995
We only have a couple of
minutes, so let's just do the 360.

1547
01:17:31,996 --> 01:17:35,399
STEVE: We're gonna bring out a
wireless camera we stole from Panasonic.

1548
01:17:35,400 --> 01:17:38,535
- (laughter)
- I'll show you what this looks like.

1549
01:17:38,536 --> 01:17:41,438
The whole thing is translucent.
You can see into it.

1550
01:17:41,439 --> 01:17:43,975
- (people muttering)
- How's that for a compromise, Woz?

1551
01:17:43,976 --> 01:17:47,544
- You still can't get into it, but you can see into it.
- Fair enough.

1552
01:17:47,545 --> 01:17:51,315
We put stereo speakers in
front, infrared right up here,

1553
01:17:51,316 --> 01:17:53,284
CD-ROM drive in the middle.

1554
01:17:53,285 --> 01:17:56,020
- (audience) Nice.
- Dual stereo headphone jacks.

1555
01:17:56,021 --> 01:17:59,257
All the connectors are inside
one beautiful little door here.

1556
01:17:59,258 --> 01:18:02,593
- (oohing and aahing)
- Ethernet. USB.

1557
01:18:02,594 --> 01:18:05,096
Even though this is a
full-blooded Macintosh,

1558
01:18:05,097 --> 01:18:06,931
we're targeting it for the number one use

1559
01:18:06,932 --> 01:18:09,432
the consumers tell us they
want a computer for, which is...

1560
01:18:09,433 --> 01:18:11,602
Let's hold it, please. Hold it.

1561
01:18:11,603 --> 01:18:14,571
- The answer was "the Internet."
- (laughter)

1562
01:18:14,572 --> 01:18:16,674
- Joanna?
- Yeah.

1563
01:18:17,808 --> 01:18:21,145
Stand in front of me. I want to look at these
quotes, but I don't want Joel to know.

1564
01:18:21,146 --> 01:18:23,349
They're all great.

1565
01:18:25,049 --> 01:18:28,151
"It is not only the coolest-looking
computer introduced in years

1566
01:18:28,152 --> 01:18:29,587
but a chest-thumping statement

1567
01:18:29,588 --> 01:18:34,727
that Silicon Valley's original dream
company is no longer somnambulant."

1568
01:18:36,394 --> 01:18:37,861
It's a word. It means "sleepwalking."

1569
01:18:37,862 --> 01:18:41,499
Steve? I'm sorry. We have to clear
the house if we're gonna start on time.

1570
01:18:41,500 --> 01:18:43,467
- We're gonna start on time.
- We're absolutely starting on time.

1571
01:18:43,468 --> 01:18:45,002
Here. Take this.

1572
01:18:45,003 --> 01:18:49,173
Everybody, that's it. They've got to
mop the stage, reset and open the house.

1573
01:18:49,174 --> 01:18:50,708
I love you guys.

1574
01:18:50,709 --> 01:18:54,580
(applause, cheering)

1575
01:18:58,951 --> 01:19:00,651
Andy, come on back a minute.

1576
01:19:00,652 --> 01:19:02,955
- Which one?
- Hertzfeld.

1577
01:19:09,428 --> 01:19:13,431
<i>Forbes</i> calls it an
"industry-altering success."

1578
01:19:13,432 --> 01:19:15,634
Look here.

1579
01:19:18,036 --> 01:19:20,236
Why haven't we ever slept together?

1580
01:19:20,237 --> 01:19:22,106
We're not in love. Look.

1581
01:19:24,175 --> 01:19:27,011
- Sculley.
- Look what he said.

1582
01:19:27,012 --> 01:19:32,383
"He has implemented the same simple strategy
that made Apple so successful 15 years ago...

1583
01:19:32,384 --> 01:19:35,621
make hit products and promote
them with terrific marketing."

1584
01:19:36,722 --> 01:19:39,190
- It was nice of him.
- It was.

1585
01:19:39,191 --> 01:19:40,691
I meant it.

1586
01:19:40,692 --> 01:19:44,261
Sightings of J.D. Salinger are
more common than John Sculley.

1587
01:19:44,262 --> 01:19:47,933
I wasn't being sarcastic.
It was nice of him.

1588
01:19:49,067 --> 01:19:51,134
- Do you talk to him?
- No.

1589
01:19:51,135 --> 01:19:53,169
You haven't talked to him since '88?

1590
01:19:53,170 --> 01:19:55,705
I'd have told you if I did.

1591
01:19:55,706 --> 01:19:57,141
Doesn't matter.

1592
01:19:57,142 --> 01:19:58,476
I don't want people
thinking they can cross me

1593
01:19:58,477 --> 01:20:02,178
- (snaps fingers)
- and then, boom, 15 years later, I'm cool with it.

1594
01:20:02,179 --> 01:20:05,182
I was kidding.

1595
01:20:05,183 --> 01:20:07,719
What's wrong with you this morning?

1596
01:20:09,054 --> 01:20:11,089
Let's get off the stage.

1597
01:20:12,656 --> 01:20:15,759
"The only thing Apple's providing
now is leadership in colors."

1598
01:20:15,760 --> 01:20:17,460
Don't worry about it.

1599
01:20:17,461 --> 01:20:19,562
- What does Bill Gates have against me?
- I don't know.

1600
01:20:19,563 --> 01:20:22,466
You're both out of your
minds. Listen to me.

1601
01:20:22,467 --> 01:20:24,535
He dropped out of a better
school than I dropped out of.

1602
01:20:24,536 --> 01:20:26,404
But he's a tool bag. I'll tell you why.

1603
01:20:26,405 --> 01:20:29,139
Make everything all right with Lisa.

1604
01:20:29,140 --> 01:20:32,343
You know, Joanna? Boundaries.

1605
01:20:32,344 --> 01:20:35,311
You've come to my apartment
at 1:00 AM and cleaned it.

1606
01:20:35,312 --> 01:20:36,713
So tell me where the boundary is.

1607
01:20:36,714 --> 01:20:38,649
- There. Let's say it's there.
- (sighs)

1608
01:20:38,650 --> 01:20:41,685
If I give you some real projections,

1609
01:20:41,686 --> 01:20:45,489
will you promise not to
repeat them from the stage?

1610
01:20:45,490 --> 01:20:48,526
What do you mean, "real projections"?

1611
01:20:48,527 --> 01:20:52,495
- What have you been giving me?
- Conservative projections.

1612
01:20:52,496 --> 01:20:54,130
Marketing's been lying to me?

1613
01:20:54,131 --> 01:20:57,802
We've been managing expectations
so that you don't not.

1614
01:20:57,803 --> 01:21:00,138
What are the real projections?

1615
01:21:01,406 --> 01:21:04,275
We're gonna sell a million
units in the first 90 days.

1616
01:21:04,276 --> 01:21:06,209
- (strikes table)
- 20,000 a month after that.

1617
01:21:06,210 --> 01:21:07,611
- Holy shit.
- Yeah.

1618
01:21:07,612 --> 01:21:09,346
You see? You wait long enough and...

1619
01:21:09,347 --> 01:21:11,749
What's more, 32% of the sales

1620
01:21:11,750 --> 01:21:15,785
are going to go to people buying
a computer for the first time.

1621
01:21:15,786 --> 01:21:20,490
And 12% are going to people using
some kind of Windows machine.

1622
01:21:20,491 --> 01:21:23,227
That's what Bill Gates has against you.

1623
01:21:24,696 --> 01:21:28,066
And it'll be the fastest-selling
computer in history.

1624
01:21:29,433 --> 01:21:31,468
You brought the company
back from life support

1625
01:21:31,469 --> 01:21:34,538
after going through the misery
of laying off 3,000 people

1626
01:21:34,539 --> 01:21:36,774
and cutting 70% of the product line.

1627
01:21:36,775 --> 01:21:40,178
So, Steven, it's over.

1628
01:21:41,780 --> 01:21:44,280
You're gonna win.

1629
01:21:44,281 --> 01:21:48,384
- It would be criminal not to enjoy this moment.
- I'm enjoying it.

1630
01:21:48,385 --> 01:21:50,420
Make things all right with Lisa.

1631
01:21:50,421 --> 01:21:52,655
- You know...
- Come on.

1632
01:21:52,656 --> 01:21:56,326
I don't like having less
privacy than other people have.

1633
01:21:56,327 --> 01:21:59,896
- Does being a multi-billionaire take some of the sting off that?
- No.

1634
01:21:59,897 --> 01:22:03,133
- All Lisa did...
- All Lisa did was give her blessing.

1635
01:22:03,134 --> 01:22:06,669
- Chrisann sold the house and...
- And Lisa could have done what?

1636
01:22:06,670 --> 01:22:09,272
How was she supposed to stop her
mother from selling her own house?

1637
01:22:09,273 --> 01:22:10,673
That I bought for the two of them.

1638
01:22:10,674 --> 01:22:12,008
How was she supposed to stop her?

1639
01:22:12,009 --> 01:22:15,612
Voicing an objection would have
been a step in the right direction.

1640
01:22:15,613 --> 01:22:18,315
You don't think you're
having a bizarre overreaction

1641
01:22:18,316 --> 01:22:21,819
to a 19-year-old girl allowing
her mother to list her own house?

1642
01:22:21,820 --> 01:22:23,053
She could've tried.

1643
01:22:23,054 --> 01:22:26,757
Was she supposed to stop her
mother, that particular mother...

1644
01:22:26,758 --> 01:22:29,826
She gave Chrisann her blessing to sell
the house and she did it to spite me.

1645
01:22:29,827 --> 01:22:33,864
I don't care if she put a
pipe bomb in the water heater.

1646
01:22:33,865 --> 01:22:36,667
You're going to fix it, now.

1647
01:22:36,668 --> 01:22:39,736
She's been acting weird for
months. She's turned on me.

1648
01:22:39,737 --> 01:22:41,804
- Fix it.
- What the...

1649
01:22:41,805 --> 01:22:43,440
Fix it, Steve.

1650
01:22:43,441 --> 01:22:44,941
- Take it easy.
- Fix it or I quit.

1651
01:22:44,942 --> 01:22:47,178
How about that? I quit,
and you never see me again.

1652
01:22:47,179 --> 01:22:49,114
How about that?

1653
01:22:50,581 --> 01:22:53,551
Tell me what's wrong with you this morning.

1654
01:22:53,552 --> 01:22:56,920
What's been wrong with me for 19 years.

1655
01:22:56,921 --> 01:22:58,888
(weeping)

1656
01:22:58,889 --> 01:23:02,860
I've been a witness, and I
tell you, I've been complicit.

1657
01:23:04,362 --> 01:23:08,365
I love you, Steve. You know how much.

1658
01:23:08,366 --> 01:23:13,369
I love that you don't care how much money a
person makes. You care <i>what</i> they make.

1659
01:23:13,370 --> 01:23:17,208
But what you make isn't supposed
to be the best part of you.

1660
01:23:17,209 --> 01:23:19,810
When you're a father,

1661
01:23:19,811 --> 01:23:22,413
that's what's supposed to
be the best part of you.

1662
01:23:22,414 --> 01:23:27,251
And it's caused me two decades of
agony, Steve, that it is for you

1663
01:23:28,920 --> 01:23:31,821
the worst.

1664
01:23:31,822 --> 01:23:37,329
(sighs) It's a little thing.
It's a very small thing.

1665
01:23:38,495 --> 01:23:40,830
(sniffles) Fix it.

1666
01:23:40,831 --> 01:23:46,236
Fix it now, or you can
contact me at my new job...

1667
01:23:46,237 --> 01:23:49,206
working anywhere I want.

1668
01:23:50,709 --> 01:23:52,977
I don't happen to think it is
a little deal. She knew that...

1669
01:23:52,978 --> 01:23:55,378
- No.
- I bought the house for the two of...

1670
01:23:55,379 --> 01:23:56,746
- No.
- What do you mean, "no"?

1671
01:23:56,747 --> 01:24:01,884
I mean no. The house has nothing
to do with why you're angry at Lisa.

1672
01:24:01,885 --> 01:24:04,887
I assure you, the house has everything
to do with why I'm angry at Lisa.

1673
01:24:04,888 --> 01:24:09,560
Have you ever heard the phrase
"reality distortion field"?

1674
01:24:09,561 --> 01:24:13,731
- Yes.
- As in "Steve's reality distortion field"?

1675
01:24:13,732 --> 01:24:16,633
I've heard it. I've read it.
It's been sung to me by Joan Baez.

1676
01:24:16,634 --> 01:24:18,401
What you call a reality distortion field,

1677
01:24:18,402 --> 01:24:20,704
and I'm pretty sure you're
the one who coined the phrase,

1678
01:24:20,705 --> 01:24:22,740
- is the reason we're here.
- I know that.

1679
01:24:22,741 --> 01:24:25,042
If I traded in my bank account for a dollar

1680
01:24:25,043 --> 01:24:27,878
every time somebody told me something
was impossible, I'd come out ahead.

1681
01:24:27,879 --> 01:24:29,913
- I know that too.
- What's the problem?

1682
01:24:29,914 --> 01:24:32,915
- My problem? It sure isn't the house.
- Jo, I...

1683
01:24:32,916 --> 01:24:37,387
It's that you told her you
weren't going to pay for Harvard.

1684
01:24:37,388 --> 01:24:39,423
That child.

1685
01:24:39,424 --> 01:24:41,825
That earnest, unironic kid.

1686
01:24:41,826 --> 01:24:43,826
She told you I wasn't paying her tuition?

1687
01:24:43,827 --> 01:24:46,496
I should have hit you with
something heavy a long time ago.

1688
01:24:46,497 --> 01:24:49,033
Lisa told you I wasn't paying her tuition?

1689
01:24:49,034 --> 01:24:53,303
- Andy told me that.
- Which one?

1690
01:24:53,304 --> 01:24:55,371
Hertzfeld.

1691
01:24:55,372 --> 01:24:56,874
How would Hertzfeld know?

1692
01:24:56,875 --> 01:25:00,910
He wrote Harvard a check for
25,000 to cover the semester.

1693
01:25:00,911 --> 01:25:03,847
Are you fucking... He paid her tuition?

1694
01:25:03,848 --> 01:25:06,717
Isn't that why you just asked to see him?

1695
01:25:06,718 --> 01:25:08,319
No, I asked to see him about something...

1696
01:25:08,320 --> 01:25:11,722
Did you tell her you weren't
going to pay for college?

1697
01:25:11,723 --> 01:25:13,723
- Yes, because...
- How could you do that?

1698
01:25:13,724 --> 01:25:16,959
Because her mother, who
is also her landlord...

1699
01:25:16,960 --> 01:25:18,928
Hertzfeld? I was ranting.

1700
01:25:18,929 --> 01:25:21,498
I was just, you know... I was
talking. You think I would...

1701
01:25:21,499 --> 01:25:25,602
I was pissed off because Lisa
was trying to piss me off, Joanna.

1702
01:25:25,603 --> 01:25:27,003
That was her intent. I don't know...

1703
01:25:27,004 --> 01:25:29,572
You obviously scared the hell out of her.

1704
01:25:29,573 --> 01:25:33,144
Hertzfeld wrote a check
to Harvard, pay for...

1705
01:25:34,345 --> 01:25:35,978
- Is she here yet?
- I'm sure she is.

1706
01:25:35,979 --> 01:25:38,348
Can you have someone bring her back?

1707
01:25:38,349 --> 01:25:40,084
Yes.

1708
01:25:40,085 --> 01:25:41,485
(exhales)

1709
01:25:41,486 --> 01:25:43,421
Thank you.

1710
01:25:46,825 --> 01:25:48,559
You know,

1711
01:25:49,994 --> 01:25:51,695
my grandmother always used to say to me...

1712
01:25:51,696 --> 01:25:54,131
I don't give a shit, Yentl.

1713
01:25:55,733 --> 01:25:57,767
- I'll have someone get Lisa.
- Thank you.

1714
01:25:57,768 --> 01:26:00,036
- And if you see Hertzfeld...
- (knocking)

1715
01:26:00,037 --> 01:26:01,972
HERTZFELD: It's Andy.

1716
01:26:01,973 --> 01:26:05,109
Speak of the devil's chief engineer.

1717
01:26:05,110 --> 01:26:06,377
Go.

1718
01:26:06,378 --> 01:26:08,412
Come on in.

1719
01:26:10,415 --> 01:26:12,383
You look great today.

1720
01:26:12,384 --> 01:26:13,851
- Thank you.
- Doesn't she?

1721
01:26:13,852 --> 01:26:17,488
She looks fantastic. Always does. Get out.

1722
01:26:19,390 --> 01:26:21,991
- Well, I think I know why I'm here.
- Do you?

1723
01:26:21,992 --> 01:26:22,726
Steve...

1724
01:26:22,727 --> 01:26:25,596
- Did you send the check yet?
- Yes.

1725
01:26:25,597 --> 01:26:28,831
So Harvard got a tuition check
from Andy Hertzfeld to pay for Lisa?

1726
01:26:28,832 --> 01:26:30,868
I don't think they look that carefully.

1727
01:26:30,869 --> 01:26:33,771
I don't think they'd notice
the check didn't come from you.

1728
01:26:33,772 --> 01:26:36,673
Close one. This was
almost embarrassing for me.

1729
01:26:36,674 --> 01:26:38,609
(sighs) I understand how...

1730
01:26:38,610 --> 01:26:40,177
I'll wire you the money today.

1731
01:26:40,178 --> 01:26:43,746
I-I understand how you feel.
And I do apologize. I do.

1732
01:26:43,747 --> 01:26:46,016
But let me tell you my thinking.

1733
01:26:46,017 --> 01:26:48,685
I can't even think of an appropriate
analogy to describe what you did.

1734
01:26:48,686 --> 01:26:51,187
I knew you guys would
fix things. You always do.

1735
01:26:51,188 --> 01:26:54,991
But in the meantime, if the money wasn't
there, she'd miss a semester of school.

1736
01:26:54,992 --> 01:26:58,728
- Yeah.
- And she'd have to tell her friends why.

1737
01:26:58,729 --> 01:27:01,197
And she needed things. She needed socks.

1738
01:27:01,198 --> 01:27:05,436
- What?
- It's cold in Cambridge. She needed warm socks.

1739
01:27:05,437 --> 01:27:10,206
- You gave her socks?
- Well, I gave her money for socks.

1740
01:27:10,207 --> 01:27:13,509
You don't get to deputize
yourself as her interim.

1741
01:27:13,510 --> 01:27:15,945
You don't get to override my
decisions. Do you understand?

1742
01:27:15,946 --> 01:27:18,115
You don't get to act
like you're her father.

1743
01:27:18,116 --> 01:27:20,683
Somebody had to.

1744
01:27:20,684 --> 01:27:22,785
What the fuck did you just say to me?

1745
01:27:22,786 --> 01:27:26,656
I've known her since she was six.

1746
01:27:26,657 --> 01:27:28,859
I also consider...

1747
01:27:28,860 --> 01:27:34,130
Chrisann's my friend, outside of what
you and I... outside of our relationship.

1748
01:27:34,131 --> 01:27:36,900
- So you're like a family adviser.
- I'm a family friend.

1749
01:27:36,901 --> 01:27:39,602
Then you probably know that
Lisa's been seeing a therapist.

1750
01:27:39,603 --> 01:27:41,170
- Yeah.
- For many years.

1751
01:27:41,171 --> 01:27:43,474
- Yeah.
- Without my knowledge.

1752
01:27:44,909 --> 01:27:46,776
That really wasn't my business.

1753
01:27:46,777 --> 01:27:50,079
(chuckles) I'm fascinated by what
you think is and isn't your business.

1754
01:27:50,080 --> 01:27:54,218
Lisa's been going to a
therapist and she likes it

1755
01:27:54,219 --> 01:27:57,855
and would love for you and
Chrisann to go with her.

1756
01:27:57,856 --> 01:28:02,493
And the reason you know that is because
you're the one that recommended the therapist.

1757
01:28:02,494 --> 01:28:04,561
Well, I know a guy.

1758
01:28:04,562 --> 01:28:08,466
No, I mean you're the one who
recommended that she see a therapist.

1759
01:28:09,634 --> 01:28:14,036
You know what? It was a while ago,
and I don't remember how the whole...

1760
01:28:14,037 --> 01:28:17,106
You told Chrisann that
Lisa should see a therapist.

1761
01:28:17,107 --> 01:28:20,244
Steve, you're stigmatizing.
It's a perfectly norm...

1762
01:28:20,245 --> 01:28:22,612
(sighs) It's not...

1763
01:28:22,613 --> 01:28:24,681
My thing was, how can it hurt?

1764
01:28:24,682 --> 01:28:26,651
Let's find out.

1765
01:28:27,719 --> 01:28:29,151
Chrisann is my friend.

1766
01:28:29,152 --> 01:28:32,522
- What was the reason you gave?
- You mean...

1767
01:28:32,523 --> 01:28:36,660
What was the reason you gave Chrisann
why Lisa should see a therapist?

1768
01:28:36,661 --> 01:28:38,794
I don't remember. We
were talking and I said...

1769
01:28:38,795 --> 01:28:42,166
It's pretty much what I just said,
that it certainly couldn't hurt.

1770
01:28:43,634 --> 01:28:47,171
You didn't say that Lisa
needed a strong male role model?

1771
01:28:54,112 --> 01:28:55,680
I did.

1772
01:29:02,253 --> 01:29:07,659
I think it's a miracle she's not robbing
banks with the Symbionese Liberation Army.

1773
01:29:10,295 --> 01:29:15,331
There's no reason in the
world why she should be nice.

1774
01:29:15,332 --> 01:29:17,535
But she is.

1775
01:29:19,937 --> 01:29:24,641
So I helped, because somebody had to.

1776
01:29:30,281 --> 01:29:33,218
I'll wire the money to you this afternoon.

1777
01:29:44,963 --> 01:29:48,130
You threatened me a long time ago.

1778
01:29:48,131 --> 01:29:49,800
Sorry?

1779
01:29:51,835 --> 01:29:54,937
A long time ago... You threatened me once.

1780
01:29:54,938 --> 01:29:57,007
People are attracted to people with talent.

1781
01:29:57,008 --> 01:29:59,209
People without it find that threatening.

1782
01:29:59,210 --> 01:30:01,277
- (snaps fingers)
- Maybe you should see a therapist.

1783
01:30:01,278 --> 01:30:03,879
Certainly couldn't hurt.

1784
01:30:03,880 --> 01:30:06,216
I meant you literally threatened me.

1785
01:30:06,217 --> 01:30:08,752
At Flint, right before the Mac launch.

1786
01:30:08,753 --> 01:30:11,053
I was recompiling. I was
trying to debug the voice demo.

1787
01:30:11,054 --> 01:30:15,392
You said if I couldn't find a solution,
you'd call me out in front of the audience.

1788
01:30:15,393 --> 01:30:17,861
- Did it say "hello"?
- It did.

1789
01:30:17,862 --> 01:30:21,263
No need to thank me.

1790
01:30:21,264 --> 01:30:25,067
Why do you want people to dislike you?

1791
01:30:25,068 --> 01:30:28,237
I don't want people to dislike me.

1792
01:30:28,238 --> 01:30:31,342
I'm indifferent to whether they dislike me.

1793
01:30:32,910 --> 01:30:35,847
Since it doesn't matter, I always have.

1794
01:30:37,180 --> 01:30:39,084
Really?

1795
01:30:40,351 --> 01:30:44,656
I've always liked you
a lot. That's too bad.

1796
01:30:46,823 --> 01:30:49,693
- Knock 'em dead.
- Thank you.

1797
01:31:11,381 --> 01:31:16,152
What is remarkable, what's
hard to fathom but true,

1798
01:31:16,153 --> 01:31:22,494
is that for a given clock rate, a PowerPC
chip is twice as fast as a Pentium II chip.

1799
01:31:31,268 --> 01:31:33,504
(glasses clatter)

1800
01:31:35,372 --> 01:31:37,541
In other words,

1801
01:31:38,742 --> 01:31:41,277
a 266 megahertz G3 chip

1802
01:31:41,278 --> 01:31:46,817
is twice as fast as a
266 megahertz Pentium II.

1803
01:31:49,853 --> 01:31:54,124
Or... a 266 G3

1804
01:31:54,125 --> 01:31:58,227
is equal to about 500 megahertz.

1805
01:31:58,228 --> 01:32:01,330
STEVE'S VOICE: <i>Do you know
what a coincidence is, Lisa?</i>

1806
01:32:01,331 --> 01:32:03,999
Take a look at <i>Byte</i>
magazine's Byte Marks,

1807
01:32:04,000 --> 01:32:06,670
- the gold standard for any...
- (knocking)

1808
01:32:11,209 --> 01:32:14,646
- Come in.
- (door opens)

1809
01:32:17,482 --> 01:32:20,182
I sent someone into the lobby.

1810
01:32:20,183 --> 01:32:22,017
- They found her, and she...
- Where is she?

1811
01:32:22,018 --> 01:32:24,887
She said she'd rather not come back.

1812
01:32:24,888 --> 01:32:27,257
- Why?
- That was it.

1813
01:32:27,258 --> 01:32:30,259
- I'm going out there myself.
- You can't. You can't.

1814
01:32:30,260 --> 01:32:32,027
It'll be a scene out of
<i>Hard Day's Night.</i>

1815
01:32:32,028 --> 01:32:34,897
- (knocking)
- (door opens)

1816
01:32:34,898 --> 01:32:37,267
- Excuse me.
- Hey, Joel.

1817
01:32:37,268 --> 01:32:39,102
Andy said it was okay to come back.

1818
01:32:39,103 --> 01:32:41,739
- Which one?
- Andy Cunningham.

1819
01:32:42,839 --> 01:32:45,808
I can't do this forever. I need
one of them to change their name.

1820
01:32:45,809 --> 01:32:47,910
You call Andy Cunningham "Andrea."

1821
01:32:47,911 --> 01:32:49,311
It doesn't matter what I call them.

1822
01:32:49,312 --> 01:32:51,047
I know who I'm talking
about when I'm talking.

1823
01:32:51,048 --> 01:32:52,915
I need everyone else to
call them different names.

1824
01:32:52,916 --> 01:32:54,952
Give me one second.

1825
01:32:59,223 --> 01:33:01,792
Can you go get her for me, please?

1826
01:33:01,793 --> 01:33:03,459
I just talked to Andy.

1827
01:33:03,460 --> 01:33:05,227
Hertzfeld.

1828
01:33:05,228 --> 01:33:08,464
I'm just trying to scrub this
out of my brain with Drano.

1829
01:33:08,465 --> 01:33:10,866
But I do want to talk to Lisa.

1830
01:33:10,867 --> 01:33:13,402
Okay. Just...

1831
01:33:13,403 --> 01:33:15,706
- Stay cool.
- Okay.

1832
01:33:18,009 --> 01:33:19,744
Thank you.

1833
01:33:27,285 --> 01:33:29,019
Hey, Steve.

1834
01:33:41,464 --> 01:33:44,834
- How are you feeling?
- I'm feeling good, Joel. How about you?

1835
01:33:44,835 --> 01:33:47,503
I don't think I could be in your
business. It changes too quickly.

1836
01:33:47,504 --> 01:33:50,841
Well, I'd hang on, 'cause yours is about
to start changing pretty quickly too.

1837
01:33:50,842 --> 01:33:54,009
This is the third time in 14
years I'm writing about you.

1838
01:33:54,010 --> 01:33:57,414
- What do you think so far?
- (knocking)

1839
01:33:57,415 --> 01:34:01,183
Excuse me. Avie's looking
for you. He has a new shark.

1840
01:34:01,184 --> 01:34:03,655
- You wanna come backstage for a second?
- JOEL: Sure.

1841
01:34:06,957 --> 01:34:10,160
- Who's this one?
- Alan Turing.

1842
01:34:10,161 --> 01:34:13,896
Single-handedly won World War II and,
for an encore, invented the computer.

1843
01:34:13,897 --> 01:34:16,098
- He won't be part of the campaign though.
- Why not?

1844
01:34:16,099 --> 01:34:18,535
'Cause you just had to ask me who he was.

1845
01:34:19,870 --> 01:34:21,838
Can I see new shark?

1846
01:34:24,375 --> 01:34:26,543
I like it better than the old shark.

1847
01:34:26,544 --> 01:34:28,178
- Sharks.
- Sharks.

1848
01:34:28,179 --> 01:34:30,079
- How many sharks did you go through?
- A couple.

1849
01:34:30,080 --> 01:34:33,883
- This is the 39th.
- We're on the record.

1850
01:34:33,884 --> 01:34:36,553
- Thirty-nine sharks.
- Okay.

1851
01:34:36,554 --> 01:34:38,621
- You know what's special about this shark?
- What?

1852
01:34:38,622 --> 01:34:43,293
No, I'm really asking, because it looks
exactly like the other 38 sharks to me.

1853
01:34:43,294 --> 01:34:45,294
STEVE: Let me see it with
the cue, from the profile.

1854
01:34:45,295 --> 01:34:47,163
WOMAN: This is cue 92-B.

1855
01:34:47,164 --> 01:34:51,368
This is a profile here, and this
is what it looks like from the back.

1856
01:34:51,369 --> 01:34:56,172
And one more thing. It eats
Pentium notebooks as a light snack.

1857
01:34:56,173 --> 01:34:59,241
This is the shark.

1858
01:34:59,242 --> 01:35:01,511
I really like it.

1859
01:35:01,512 --> 01:35:03,312
Nobody gets it right the first time,

1860
01:35:03,313 --> 01:35:05,915
but I should have been shown
this shark 15, 20 fish ago.

1861
01:35:05,916 --> 01:35:07,616
- You probably were.
- Lock it in.

1862
01:35:07,617 --> 01:35:09,451
Ten minutes.

1863
01:35:09,452 --> 01:35:13,956
He killed himself by taking a bite
of a poison apple... Alan Turing.

1864
01:35:13,957 --> 01:35:15,091
Yeah.

1865
01:35:15,092 --> 01:35:17,694
There should be statues of that man.

1866
01:35:17,695 --> 01:35:20,062
His name should be on the
lips of schoolchildren.

1867
01:35:20,063 --> 01:35:23,633
The rainbow flag apple with a bite
taken out... That's where it came from?

1868
01:35:23,634 --> 01:35:26,503
No, we picked it off a list
of friendly-sounding words.

1869
01:35:26,504 --> 01:35:29,472
But wouldn't it be great if that
had been the story behind it?

1870
01:35:29,473 --> 01:35:33,075
Steve. Kinda liked the last shark.

1871
01:35:33,076 --> 01:35:35,011
- AVIE: Fuck you.
- (chuckles)

1872
01:35:35,012 --> 01:35:36,612
I wanted to ask you a favor.

1873
01:35:36,613 --> 01:35:37,813
My friend, a long time ago,

1874
01:35:37,814 --> 01:35:40,583
you asked me a favor before a
product launch, and I said no.

1875
01:35:40,584 --> 01:35:43,018
- You wanted me to acknowledge...
- Hang on.

1876
01:35:43,019 --> 01:35:47,289
If you're about to say you were wrong,
I want to prepare this journalist.

1877
01:35:47,290 --> 01:35:51,628
I was 100% right, and you
were spectacularly wrong.

1878
01:35:51,629 --> 01:35:54,129
But I still owe you a favor, so name it.

1879
01:35:54,130 --> 01:35:55,697
(sighs) Steve...

1880
01:35:55,698 --> 01:36:00,369
- It can't be acknowledging the Apple II team.
- Acknowledge the Apple II team.

1881
01:36:00,370 --> 01:36:02,172
- How about in private?
- No.

1882
01:36:02,173 --> 01:36:03,606
- Is this a prank?
- No.

1883
01:36:03,607 --> 01:36:05,741
I'm trying to remember that
a 300 megahertz G3 chip...

1884
01:36:05,742 --> 01:36:08,012
Just the top guys.

1885
01:36:10,380 --> 01:36:12,082
Steve.

1886
01:36:15,119 --> 01:36:16,686
- Excuse me, okay?
- Yep.

1887
01:36:16,687 --> 01:36:19,188
One second.

1888
01:36:19,189 --> 01:36:21,691
(clears throat)

1889
01:36:21,692 --> 01:36:26,096
- She said she'd rather not.
- What do you mean?

1890
01:36:26,097 --> 01:36:29,432
She's sitting with her friends, and
she said she'd rather not come back.

1891
01:36:29,433 --> 01:36:31,433
Okay. Tell her... Take her aside.

1892
01:36:31,434 --> 01:36:33,436
I don't want to embarrass
her in front of her friends.

1893
01:36:33,437 --> 01:36:35,672
But tell her I just scared
the shit out of Andy,

1894
01:36:35,673 --> 01:36:38,209
and this time, nobody's
paying her fucking...

1895
01:36:39,477 --> 01:36:41,544
All right. Don't say that.

1896
01:36:41,545 --> 01:36:44,146
But do your thing where
you sound old and wise

1897
01:36:44,147 --> 01:36:47,417
because of the broad, tragic
European canvas of your life.

1898
01:36:47,418 --> 01:36:50,285
You know I wasn't born in a
19th-century shtetl, right?

1899
01:36:50,286 --> 01:36:52,454
Please tell her it's important.

1900
01:36:52,455 --> 01:36:55,025
- Everything all right?
- Yeah.

1901
01:36:55,026 --> 01:36:56,625
- There are people around here, man...
- I know.

1902
01:36:56,626 --> 01:37:00,562
- Including a member of the press.
- I see him.

1903
01:37:00,563 --> 01:37:01,664
Woz.

1904
01:37:01,665 --> 01:37:04,936
Just the top guys, the ones
who are getting laid off.

1905
01:37:06,137 --> 01:37:08,405
(clears throat) Listen, okay?

1906
01:37:08,406 --> 01:37:13,343
Last year, Apple lost one billion dollars.

1907
01:37:13,344 --> 01:37:15,311
I don't even know how that's possible.

1908
01:37:15,312 --> 01:37:17,780
You were less than 90
days from being insolvent.

1909
01:37:17,781 --> 01:37:20,583
I had three different accountants
try to explain it to me.

1910
01:37:20,584 --> 01:37:23,585
The whole place has to be streamlined.

1911
01:37:23,586 --> 01:37:26,188
- Start with two of the accountants.
- I started with the...

1912
01:37:26,189 --> 01:37:29,225
- Joel, could you come offstage? We're gonna go backstage.
- Leave him right there.

1913
01:37:29,226 --> 01:37:33,596
I started with the Apple II team
because we don't make that anymore.

1914
01:37:33,597 --> 01:37:37,333
- Just acknowledge the top guys.
- Have a mimosa and relax.

1915
01:37:37,334 --> 01:37:39,835
You will not blow me off right now, Steve.

1916
01:37:39,836 --> 01:37:42,605
- The top guys deserve...
- There are no top guys.

1917
01:37:42,606 --> 01:37:45,208
All right? On the Apple II
team, there are no top guys.

1918
01:37:45,209 --> 01:37:48,645
They're "B" players, and "B"
players discourage the "A" players.

1919
01:37:48,646 --> 01:37:50,612
I want "A" players at Apple and not Dell.

1920
01:37:50,613 --> 01:37:53,348
They're not "B" players, and
I'm a better judge of that.

1921
01:37:53,349 --> 01:37:55,819
Less than 90 days from insolvency,

1922
01:37:55,820 --> 01:37:59,588
in part because somebody thought
the Newton wasn't a box of garbage.

1923
01:37:59,589 --> 01:38:01,223
- Joel, could you come offstage, please?
- Leave him.

1924
01:38:01,224 --> 01:38:02,659
I'm talking about...

1925
01:38:02,660 --> 01:38:05,261
You guys designed and shipped a
little box of garbage while I was gone.

1926
01:38:05,262 --> 01:38:06,728
I'm talking about the Apple II,

1927
01:38:06,729 --> 01:38:09,531
which is not just a crucial
part of this company's history,

1928
01:38:09,532 --> 01:38:12,102
it is a crucial part of the
history of personal computing.

1929
01:38:12,103 --> 01:38:13,770
For a time.

1930
01:38:13,771 --> 01:38:16,371
The least you can do, if you're
going to downsize these people...

1931
01:38:16,372 --> 01:38:19,174
They're gonna live in the biggest houses
of anyone on the unemployment line.

1932
01:38:19,175 --> 01:38:23,480
Is to acknowledge them. Acknowledge
them and the Apple II during this launch.

1933
01:38:23,481 --> 01:38:25,048
This is a new animal.

1934
01:38:25,049 --> 01:38:29,185
This whole place was built by the Apple
II. <i>You</i> were built by the Apple II.

1935
01:38:29,186 --> 01:38:32,254
As a matter of fact, I was destroyed
by the Apple II and its open system

1936
01:38:32,255 --> 01:38:34,124
so that hackers and hobbyists

1937
01:38:34,125 --> 01:38:37,593
could build ham radios or something.

1938
01:38:37,594 --> 01:38:39,395
And then it nearly destroyed Apple

1939
01:38:39,396 --> 01:38:41,431
when you spent all your money on it

1940
01:38:41,432 --> 01:38:44,700
and developed a grand
total of no new products.

1941
01:38:44,701 --> 01:38:46,669
- The Newton.
- The little box of garbage.

1942
01:38:46,670 --> 01:38:50,775
You guys came up with the Newton.
You want people to know that?

1943
01:38:52,675 --> 01:38:56,146
This is a product launch, not a luncheon.

1944
01:38:56,147 --> 01:38:58,248
The last thing I want to
do is connect the iMac to...

1945
01:38:58,249 --> 01:39:01,217
WOZNIAK: To the only successful
product that this company has ever made.

1946
01:39:01,218 --> 01:39:04,654
I'm sorry to be blunt, but
that happens to be the truth.

1947
01:39:04,655 --> 01:39:08,624
The Lisa was a failure.
The Macintosh was a failure.

1948
01:39:08,625 --> 01:39:10,692
I don't like talking like this,

1949
01:39:10,693 --> 01:39:15,431
but I am tired of being
Ringo when I know I was John.

1950
01:39:15,432 --> 01:39:16,833
Everybody loves Ringo.

1951
01:39:16,834 --> 01:39:19,903
And I'm tired of being patronized by you.

1952
01:39:21,705 --> 01:39:24,339
You think John became John
by winning a raffle, Woz?

1953
01:39:24,340 --> 01:39:25,708
You think he tricked somebody

1954
01:39:25,709 --> 01:39:28,311
or hit George Harrison over the head?

1955
01:39:28,312 --> 01:39:30,245
He was John because he was John.

1956
01:39:30,246 --> 01:39:34,584
He was John 'cause he wrote "Ticket
to Ride." And I wrote the Apple II.

1957
01:39:34,585 --> 01:39:38,122
- Everybody? I want to clear the auditorium.
- Nobody moves.

1958
01:39:40,456 --> 01:39:42,292
You made a beautiful board,

1959
01:39:42,293 --> 01:39:44,427
which, by the way, you were
willing to give out for free,

1960
01:39:44,428 --> 01:39:46,495
so don't tell me how you built Apple.

1961
01:39:46,496 --> 01:39:48,897
If it weren't for me, you'd be the
easiest "A" at Homestead High School.

1962
01:39:48,898 --> 01:39:53,203
These people live and die by your
praise, so here's your chance.

1963
01:39:53,204 --> 01:39:58,241
Acknowledge that something good happened
that you weren't in the room for.

1964
01:40:01,378 --> 01:40:03,612
- No.
- Steve.

1965
01:40:03,613 --> 01:40:08,184
Do it. It's right. It's...

1966
01:40:09,820 --> 01:40:11,353
It's right.

1967
01:40:11,354 --> 01:40:13,489
Sorry, but no.

1968
01:40:13,490 --> 01:40:16,892
Then let me put it another way.

1969
01:40:16,893 --> 01:40:19,795
I don't think there's a man
who's done more to advance

1970
01:40:19,796 --> 01:40:23,333
the democratization that comes
with personal computing than I have,

1971
01:40:23,334 --> 01:40:24,901
but you've never had any respect for me.

1972
01:40:24,902 --> 01:40:27,004
Now why is that?

1973
01:40:28,272 --> 01:40:29,638
I'd at least consider the possibility

1974
01:40:29,639 --> 01:40:31,673
that it's because you've
never had any for me.

1975
01:40:31,674 --> 01:40:33,977
(door opens)

1976
01:40:33,978 --> 01:40:35,712
What the hell is going on here?

1977
01:40:35,713 --> 01:40:39,183
Nothing. Thank you for your time.

1978
01:40:42,686 --> 01:40:45,788
It's done. She's coming back.

1979
01:40:45,789 --> 01:40:48,358
You came a half-inch from putting
this company out of business.

1980
01:40:49,927 --> 01:40:52,162
Now who do I see about that?

1981
01:40:53,296 --> 01:40:55,498
I'm letting you keep your job.

1982
01:40:55,499 --> 01:40:57,902
You get a pass.

1983
01:41:00,403 --> 01:41:01,803
You know, when people used to ask me

1984
01:41:01,804 --> 01:41:04,374
what the difference was
between me and Steve Jobs,

1985
01:41:04,375 --> 01:41:07,477
I would say Steve was the big-picture guy

1986
01:41:07,478 --> 01:41:09,411
and I liked a solid workbench.

1987
01:41:09,412 --> 01:41:11,414
When people ask me what
the difference is now,

1988
01:41:11,415 --> 01:41:13,850
I say "Steve's an asshole."

1989
01:41:13,851 --> 01:41:16,652
Your products are better
than you are, brother.

1990
01:41:16,653 --> 01:41:19,621
That's the idea, brother.

1991
01:41:19,622 --> 01:41:23,459
And knowing that, that's the difference.

1992
01:41:23,460 --> 01:41:26,462
It's not binary.

1993
01:41:26,463 --> 01:41:30,034
You can be decent and
gifted at the same time.

1994
01:41:51,722 --> 01:41:53,856
JOANNA: He didn't mean it.

1995
01:41:53,857 --> 01:41:55,960
Yeah, he did.

1996
01:41:58,429 --> 01:42:00,397
He's a temperamental guy.

1997
01:42:01,598 --> 01:42:03,300
No, he's not.

1998
01:42:06,870 --> 01:42:10,505
(scoffs) It's like five
minutes before every launch,

1999
01:42:10,506 --> 01:42:14,677
everyone goes to a bar, gets drunk
and tells me what they really think.

2000
01:42:14,678 --> 01:42:17,414
- (sighs)
- She's coming to your dressing room.

2001
01:42:28,025 --> 01:42:30,426
JOANNA: I told you to make
things all right with Lisa.

2002
01:42:30,427 --> 01:42:33,730
I didn't say you had to settle
every blood feud you have.

2003
01:42:33,731 --> 01:42:37,767
STEVE: Last time blood feuds weren't
settled, I lost the cover of <i>Time.</i>

2004
01:42:37,768 --> 01:42:41,471
Though for the life of me, I still don't know
what the hell Dan Kottke was mad at me about.

2005
01:42:41,472 --> 01:42:44,139
- Kottke didn't lose you the cover of <i>Time.</i>
- Of course he did.

2006
01:42:44,140 --> 01:42:46,776
Would you like me to demonstrate
your capacity to be wrong

2007
01:42:46,777 --> 01:42:48,378
when you're certain you're right?

2008
01:42:48,379 --> 01:42:50,847
Dan Kottke told <i>Time</i>
magazine that I was denying...

2009
01:42:50,848 --> 01:42:52,615
Do you remember the cover?

2010
01:42:52,616 --> 01:42:54,150
- Of <i>Time?</i>
- Yes.

2011
01:42:54,151 --> 01:42:55,918
- Yes.
- What was it?

2012
01:42:55,919 --> 01:42:57,986
- What are you talking about?
- What was on the cover?

2013
01:42:57,987 --> 01:42:59,588
- A computer.
- No.

2014
01:42:59,589 --> 01:43:01,990
It was a sculpture of a computer.

2015
01:43:01,991 --> 01:43:04,561
It was a sculpture.

2016
01:43:05,696 --> 01:43:08,865
<i>Time</i> would have had to have
commissioned it months in advance.

2017
01:43:08,866 --> 01:43:11,066
You were never in the
conversation for Man of the Year.

2018
01:43:11,067 --> 01:43:12,768
Nobody lost you anything.

2019
01:43:12,769 --> 01:43:14,637
STEVE'S VOICE: <i>...picture
of me and the Mac.</i>

2020
01:43:14,638 --> 01:43:17,673
So what else are you sure about?

2021
01:43:17,674 --> 01:43:20,575
I don't know how I could've missed that.

2022
01:43:20,576 --> 01:43:22,611
- Reality distortion.
- No, seriously.

2023
01:43:22,612 --> 01:43:23,812
Seriously.

2024
01:43:23,813 --> 01:43:26,615
Don't try to win an argument with Lisa.

2025
01:43:26,616 --> 01:43:29,752
- Just say you were wrong.
- (knocking)

2026
01:43:29,753 --> 01:43:31,856
Come on in, honey.

2027
01:43:32,889 --> 01:43:35,424
- It's not "honey."
- John.

2028
01:43:35,425 --> 01:43:37,627
Get in. Get in. Get out of the hall.

2029
01:43:37,628 --> 01:43:39,061
I was taken in a side entrance.

2030
01:43:39,062 --> 01:43:40,963
I'll go out the same
way. No one will see me.

2031
01:43:40,964 --> 01:43:43,566
- How are you, Joanna?
- I'm good, John.

2032
01:43:43,567 --> 01:43:46,102
I'm just surprised to see you.

2033
01:43:46,103 --> 01:43:48,704
Everyone here really appreciates
the quote you gave to <i>Forbes.</i>

2034
01:43:48,705 --> 01:43:51,507
- You didn't have to do that.
- My pleasure.

2035
01:43:51,508 --> 01:43:54,544
JOANNA: If you want, I can slip you in
the back once the house lights go out.

2036
01:43:54,545 --> 01:43:57,548
- JOHN: I'm just here to say "good luck."
- <i>Okay.</i>

2037
01:43:58,915 --> 01:44:00,917
You just have a couple of minutes.

2038
01:44:00,918 --> 01:44:03,254
- Would you try to find...
- Yeah.

2039
01:44:07,457 --> 01:44:09,559
You're a good man, John.

2040
01:44:11,128 --> 01:44:13,530
(door opens)

2041
01:44:15,566 --> 01:44:17,501
(door closes)

2042
01:44:21,905 --> 01:44:25,040
So I brought you a present.

2043
01:44:25,041 --> 01:44:26,709
STEVE: A Newton.

2044
01:44:26,710 --> 01:44:32,514
Don't take it out of the box, you'll be able
to sell it, which is more than I can say.

2045
01:44:32,515 --> 01:44:34,484
Everything all right there?

2046
01:44:34,485 --> 01:44:36,752
Uh, no... (clears throat)

2047
01:44:36,753 --> 01:44:39,754
Just something Joanna pointed out to me.

2048
01:44:39,755 --> 01:44:43,025
I missed something so obvious about...

2049
01:44:43,026 --> 01:44:44,628
Doesn't matter.

2050
01:44:46,629 --> 01:44:50,098
Look, Wall Street's gonna sit back
and wait to see how you do as CEO,

2051
01:44:50,099 --> 01:44:52,968
so don't let any fluctuation
bother you for the first 12 months.

2052
01:44:52,969 --> 01:44:55,472
Day traders are gonna respond.

2053
01:44:56,506 --> 01:44:58,409
I don't need to school you.

2054
01:44:59,643 --> 01:45:01,843
This your way of telling me I
shouldn't have killed the Newton?

2055
01:45:01,844 --> 01:45:06,281
The most efficient animal
on the planet is the condor.

2056
01:45:06,282 --> 01:45:09,084
The most inefficient animals
on the planet are humans.

2057
01:45:09,085 --> 01:45:11,853
(chuckles) Well, you shouldn't
have killed it for spite.

2058
01:45:11,854 --> 01:45:15,290
That's bad business. Don't do that.

2059
01:45:15,291 --> 01:45:20,663
But a human with a bicycle
becomes the most efficient animal.

2060
01:45:20,664 --> 01:45:22,798
And the right computer...

2061
01:45:22,799 --> 01:45:25,601
a friendly, easy computer
that isn't an eyesore

2062
01:45:25,602 --> 01:45:30,071
but rather sits on your desk with
the beauty of a Tensor lamp...

2063
01:45:30,072 --> 01:45:35,076
The right computer will
be a bicycle for the mind.

2064
01:45:35,077 --> 01:45:37,679
Do you like it?

2065
01:45:37,680 --> 01:45:40,081
I was giving back.

2066
